<pb n="9">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546814</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Agony in the Garden</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546814</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Agony in the Garden</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000002</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000002</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Agony in the Garden</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">She sat by the window</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Her face expressionless,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Fingers moving in slow</l>
<l ln="4        ">Surrender at her dress.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="5        ">Hot summer lay around</l>
<l ln="6        ">And the pregnable rose</l>
<l ln="7        ">Lifts her head from the ground</l>
<l ln="8        ">For the passionate nose.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">In a bush, a thrush sings</l>
<l ln="10      ">Evangelical lays;</l>
<l ln="11      ">His mate, drooping her wings</l>
<l ln="12      ">Is consumed by a phrase.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">Alone with her distress</l>
<l ln="14      ">And her heart all aflame,</l>
<l ln="15      ">She's unable to bless</l>
<l ln="16      ">And unwilling to blame.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="17      ">All her whites shall be grey</l>
<l ln="18      ">And her window panes black</l>
<l ln="19      ">All her teeth shall decay</l>
<l ln="20      ">And her skin shall grow slack.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="21      ">And a sword pierce her gut</l>
<l ln="22      ">Cleave her flesh to the bone</l>
<l ln="23      ">And the devil shall cut</l>
<l ln="24      ">Out her heart for his own.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="10">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546815</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>For Grandma</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546815</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>For Grandma</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000003</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000003</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>For Grandma</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">In the twilight of her time,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">When every day was dumb</l>
<l ln="3        ">And what was said was not received,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Letters spoke of &ldquo;sickness, the crime</l>
<l ln="5        ">Of growing old, head grown numb,</l>
<l ln="6        ">The cold, boredom unrelieved.&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="7        ">We wrote spasmodically,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Duty bound. &ldquo;Children are well,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Don't get round to writing much, we</l>
<l ln="10      ">Apologise.&rdquo; Did we tell</l>
<l ln="11      ">You of the racked brain and mind</l>
<l ln="12      ">To find words cursory but kind?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">No more will rain spoil your day</l>
<l ln="14      ">With spite, nor wind waken you</l>
<l ln="15      ">At night, with its malicious play.</l>
<l ln="16      ">The word became flesh and grew,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Assumed a malignant form,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Kept your faded spirits warm.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546816</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Under the Hammer</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546816</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Under the Hammer</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000004</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000004</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Under the Hammer</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">The reduced nanny, smell of talcum powder</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Still in her nose, opened her napkin soft heart.</l>
<l ln="3        ">The mistress liked things nice. The breakfast tray</l>
<l ln="4        ">Laid so, her bath regular as milking time,</l>
<l ln="5        ">The <hi r="italic">Telegraph</hi> to graze upon at ten.</l>
<l ln="6        ">Life the same, yesterday, today, forever.</l>
<l ln="7        ">The horrors of war had proved most bleak,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Cat food had been so difficult to get.</l>
<l ln="9        ">Society evacuating its fecal</l>
<l ln="10      ">Strata into her house, had caused acute</l>
<l ln="11      ">Discomfort to the family doctor.</l>
<l ln="12      ">Life and the evening sky seemed set for sunshine.</l>
<pb n="11">
<l ln="13      ">But came the fat, bullying son&hyphen;in&hyphen;law,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Given to public anger, impervious</l>
<l ln="15      ">To the subtle snub and well bred silences.</l>
<l ln="16      ">Took first the favourite daughter, then the farm,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Crumbled her comfort in his hammer mill,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Offered the solicitor violence.</l>
<l ln="19      ">Now she stumbles in a haze of spirit,</l>
<l ln="20      ">With two well&hyphen;hung dogs, the neutral common.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546817</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Happy New Year</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546817</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Happy New Year</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000005</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000005</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Happy New Year</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Let us assess the first month of the year,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">One heavy cold, a Brahms occasioned tear,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Five slips expressing editors' regrets,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Eight games of snooker, half a dozen bets,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Two visits from the curate who with skill</l>
<l ln="6        ">Unwittingly disseminates ill&hyphen;will.</l>
<l ln="7        ">Two eyes to watch my daughters grow and bless,</l>
<l ln="8        ">One wild mad tongue to lash them to distress,</l>
<l ln="9        ">A sudden sigh for people in the street,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Rude thoughts about the butcher and his meat.</l>
<l ln="11      ">We don't know where we go but on we plod,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Pursued by lust and shame and nudged by God.</l>
<l ln="13      ">It seems this bright New Year bids fair to be</l>
<l ln="14      ">Full of fertility, but not for me.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546818</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Culture</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546818</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Culture</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000006</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000006</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Culture</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">We talked; it seemed my northern accent hung</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">A curtain of cloth caps and tripes between us,</l>
<l ln="3        ">You determined in your missionary zeal</l>
<l ln="4        ">I with a subtle plan for a seduction.</l>
<l ln="5        ">Against the gorgeous month you spent in Rome</l>
<l ln="6        ">I set wet weekends on the pier at Whitby.</l>
<pb n="12">
<l ln="7        ">We talked, my God we talked and all the time,</l>
<l ln="8        ">My clumsy farmer's fingers hurt your soul.</l>
<l ln="9        ">The suit I wore, a smart new Co&hyphen;op check</l>
<l ln="10      ">Paid a poor dividend compared to daddy's.</l>
<l ln="11      ">The night crept on, my bones embalmed in gin</l>
<l ln="12      ">Grew less insistent in their urge for sin.</l>
<l ln="13      ">You were too nice, too earnest and too kind</l>
<l ln="14      ">For the crude, virile game I had in mind,</l>
<l ln="15      ">I was too moral, tired, bored and mean</l>
<l ln="16      ">To keep you from your <hi r="italic">London Magazine.</hi></l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546819</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Police Description</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546819</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Police Description</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000007</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000007</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Police Description</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Measured heel to head I register</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Six feet one inch with a nude foot.</l>
<l ln="3        ">My weight, thirteen stones, kept in the middle</l>
<l ln="4        ">From riotous expansion by a steel and canvas belt,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Socially a right and proper distinction.</l>
<l ln="6        ">I suffer in the flesh under the accepted sins:</l>
<l ln="7        ">Lust, greed and tyranny wage an unending war</l>
<l ln="8        ">Within my bowels and boundaries,</l>
<l ln="9        ">I have my erections and my crucifictions,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Despair and sometimes a tiny candle of triumph.</l>
<l ln="11      ">In this very desirable property</l>
<l ln="12      ">With its fertile gardens and thick woods</l>
<l ln="13      ">I live in a small room with two little windows.</l>
<l ln="14      ">Crouched in this bedsittingroom I spend my days,</l>
<l ln="15      ">Seldom venturing into my estate.</l>
<l ln="16      ">To every face I meet I make my demand,</l>
<l ln="17      ">&ldquo;For Christ's sake reconstruct me with love.&rdquo;</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="13">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546820</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Fountains Abbey</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546820</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Fountains Abbey</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000008</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000008</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Fountains Abbey</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">We start as all the popular programmes start</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">With the commercials at the gate, the picture postcards,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Presents, films, the omnipresent lolly</l>
<l ln="4        ">Clutters up our history with our past.</l>
<l ln="5        ">In natural sequence to the world of commerce,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Authority demands its twentieth of a poem</l>
<l ln="7        ">To let the inheritors view their heritage.</l>
<l ln="8        ">All formal rites performed we now are free&mdash;to enter</l>
<l ln="9        ">And wander down to where a restless river</l>
<l ln="10      ">Fails to bear all our sins away.</l>
<l ln="11      ">There in the soft green meadow, mellow in the sun,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Stone upon prayer upon torn finger nail feels for the heavens</l>
<l ln="13      ">And crumbles in its own inadequacy.</l>
<l ln="14      ">My daughter asks, how many men have died</l>
<l ln="15      ">Creating this high monument to pride?</l>
<l ln="16      ">God knows! If all the men who died in its defence,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Were laid&mdash;with proper reverence&mdash;side by side</l>
<l ln="18      ">Within its longest shadow, this shallow valley</l>
<l ln="19      ">Would be levelled to its highest hill.</l>
<l ln="20      ">And still they come the concubines of truth.</l>
<l ln="21      ">The machinist, standing on the Abbot's tomb,</l>
<l ln="22      ">Baring her teeth into the camera's eye,</l>
<l ln="23      ">Has poised stiletto heels above his heart,</l>
<l ln="24      ">And in the infected blood the world may see</l>
<l ln="25      ">The adumbration of its history.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546821</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Please Don't Laugh</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546821</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Please Don't Laugh</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000009</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000009</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Please Don't Laugh</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">I have given up trying to be grown up</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And spend my time in adolescent joys:</l>
<l ln="3        ">Finally thrown my &ldquo;I am Jesus&rdquo; face off</l>
<l ln="4        ">And gone out to the boozer with the boys.</l></pdiv>
<pb n="14">
<pdiv><l ln="5        ">One time I took my stand a little distant</l>
<l ln="6        ">Listened to their jokes and felt superior,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Quivered at the mention of a pair of tits,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Coloured from my toe to my posterior.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">For many years I looked round for a model</l>
<l ln="10      ">And two or three times thought I had found one,</l>
<l ln="11      ">But when I tried to pin them down for study,</l>
<l ln="12      ">A boy remained, I found the man had gone.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">The first one had a pride that stank like mine did</l>
<l ln="14      ">The second had a nibble with a tart,</l>
<l ln="15      ">The third one curried favour with the wealthy</l>
<l ln="16      ">The fourth, poor sod, became obsessed with art.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="17      ">One more said that he would pin his faith in love</l>
<l ln="18      ">To rid the world of adolescent strife,</l>
<l ln="19      ">But quickly called me outside for a punch&hyphen;up</l>
<l ln="20      ">When some kind neighbour said I'd jumped his wife.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="21      ">My mother thought the world was growing rotten,</l>
<l ln="22      ">That God would take His loved ones for His own</l>
<l ln="23      ">&mdash;Perhaps that's why I sometimes feel so lonely</l>
<l ln="24      ">Playing blues records on the gramophone.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="25      ">Last week I went out walking in the country</l>
<l ln="26      ">And heard the turtle&hyphen;dove call from a tree,</l>
<l ln="27      ">I didn't stop to listen to his love&hyphen;song</l>
<l ln="28      ">I knew he wasn't singing it to me.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="29      ">As I came home I had to pass a cripple</l>
<l ln="30      ">I thought I ought to smile as I went by,</l>
<l ln="31      ">&ldquo;Now there's someone that you should try and love, son&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="32      ">I walked straight past, I couldn't meet her eye.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="33      ">A candidate for office came to our house</l>
<l ln="34      ">&ldquo;Just look and see, sir, what my party's done&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="35      ">I pointed to a block of flats like barracks</l>
<l ln="36      ">And trees that stood there weeping for the sun.</l></pdiv>
<pb n="15">
<pdiv><l ln="37      ">Kind Dr Best's the one who'll cure my sickness</l>
<l ln="38      ">In his still waiting&hyphen;room I sit and pray,</l>
<l ln="39      ">He'll give me Soneryl to help the night on</l>
<l ln="40      ">And heart&hyphen;shaped Drinamyl to cheer the day.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="41      ">So farewell to the purple&hyphen;headed mountain</l>
<l ln="42      ">The family house, the river running by,</l>
<l ln="43      ">Exotic over&hyphen;ripe fruits in the winter</l>
<l ln="44      ">The atom bomb that lightens up the sky.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="45      ">O Father will you cross my brow with water</l>
<l ln="46      ">And place my tired hands upon my chest,</l>
<l ln="47      ">Remove my testicles and their appendage</l>
<l ln="48      ">And teach me how to love with what is left.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546822</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Exercising the Dog</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546822</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Exercising the Dog</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000010</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000010</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Exercising the Dog</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Green fingers float in the air,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Under a flawless sky</l>
<l ln="3        ">The dying flowers walk,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Summer eyes impale me.</l>
<l ln="5        ">&indent;Discipline the hand</l>
<l ln="6        ">Keep the mind on gardens</l>
<l ln="7        ">Deny in silence all the spoken lies,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Smile at strangers.</l>
<l ln="9        ">&indent;O gentle, tender heart</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;Bless this warm salt tear</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;Furnish an empty room.</l>
<l ln="12      ">Tongue to beseeching tongue</l>
<l ln="13      ">Perform the evening sacrifice</l>
<l ln="14      ">Add emphasis with words</l>
<l ln="15      ">Move down the tightening thigh</l>
<l ln="16      ">With rapacious hand</l>
<l ln="17      ">Manipulate the nipple</l>
<l ln="18      ">&indent;O Lord Jesus grant me this night.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="16">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546823</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>A Beginning</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546823</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>A Beginning</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000011</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000011</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Beginning</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Turning the pages of your magazine</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Your tiny mind blurred by this modern dullness</l>
<l ln="3        ">You see that trees are wood and water wet.</l>
<l ln="4        ">Marvel at this my young friend while you may,</l>
<l ln="5        ">For one day you will wake to find that trees</l>
<l ln="6        ">Are question marks or figures of reproach</l>
<l ln="7        ">And piping in their bare and barren branches,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Or singing songs of sorrow in the spring,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Ex&hyphen;angels of the Lord speak of lost heaven.</l>
<l ln="10      ">Then you will find your thoughts will turn to water,</l>
<l ln="11      ">That special liquid from the crystal stream,</l>
<l ln="12      ">No longer water but the grace of God.</l>
<l ln="13      ">How can you mix water with that rancid joy</l>
<l ln="14      ">That sees a tree as wood and water wet?</l>
<l ln="15      ">I thank you Lord for my uncertainties.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546824</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Evensong</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546824</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Evensong</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000012</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000012</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Evensong</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">You ask &ldquo;what has gone wrong,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Where are the day's soft touches</l>
<l ln="3        ">And evensong?&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="4        ">You sigh for urgent hands</l>
<l ln="5        ">For flustered blood&hyphen;filled faces</l>
<l ln="6        ">And promised lands.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="7        ">Time was when urgent feet</l>
<l ln="8        ">Were felt in the waiting flesh</l>
<l ln="9        ">Far down the street,</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="10      ">When we so flail of fire</l>
<l ln="11      ">Performed our night oblations</l>
<l ln="12      ">In day attire,</l></pdiv>
<pb n="17">
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">Feeling it not remiss</l>
<l ln="14      ">To ease the pressures with a</l>
<l ln="15      ">Clerical kiss</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="16      ">Indiscreet in a room</l>
<l ln="17      ">Where antelopes are poised</l>
<l ln="18      ">And roses bloom.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="19      ">Why, my dear, could you not be</l>
<l ln="20      ">Content with possessing the</l>
<l ln="21      ">External me</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="22      ">But hanker in your heart</l>
<l ln="23      ">For that rich pearl with which</l>
<l ln="24      ">I cannot part.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="25      ">Trapped in the flesh and bone</l>
<l ln="26      ">The light of the world watches</l>
<l ln="27      ">And weeps alone.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546825</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Plea for a Decent Death</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546825</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Plea for a Decent Death</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000013</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000013</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Plea for a Decent Death</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">There are comers of this town</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Where I have no wish to die;</l>
<l ln="3        ">Outside the Salvation Army Citadel</l>
<l ln="4        ">For instance, or in the cheaper shopping centre.</l>
<l ln="5        ">To come face to face with my Maker</l>
<l ln="6        ">After carefully stage managing</l>
<l ln="7        ">My disastrous and unsuccessful life,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Dressed in a Burtons suit, in a setting</l>
<l ln="9        ">Unworthy of my ambition</l>
<l ln="10      ">Would be high farce or great tragedy,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Something I have spent a lifetime avoiding.</l>
<l ln="12      ">Can one look at death objectively?</l>
<l ln="13      ">The trouble is one is so terribly involved.</l>
<l ln="14      ">From the slimy skinned rabbit</l>
<l ln="15      ">Making its first and formal protest,</l>
<pb n="18">
<l ln="16      ">To the shambling, backward looking reprobate</l>
<l ln="17      ">Regurgitating his old sins,</l>
<l ln="18      ">One and all are committed to death.</l>
<l ln="19      ">So when I die let me die with dignity</l>
<l ln="20      ">On Saturday, bathed and wearing a clean vest,</l>
<l ln="21      ">Unloved perhaps and unmourned</l>
<l ln="22      ">But with a paid up policy</l>
<l ln="23      ">And walking in the &ldquo;nicer&rdquo; parts of town.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546826</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>All Had Seemed Propitious for the Harvest</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546826</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>All Had Seemed Propitious for the Harvest</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000014</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000014</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>All Had Seemed Propitious for the Harvest</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">All had seemed propitious for the harvest</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The winter frosts had broken down the day;</l>
<l ln="3        ">Safe in the barn the seed was bagged and dressed</l>
<l ln="4        ">Ditches were dug, the sun shone all the day;</l>
<l ln="5        ">Last year the orchard had been pruned for fruit.</l>
<l ln="6        ">Only a lack of brains distinguishes the brute,</l>
<l ln="7        ">I had forgotten my fine flesh would decay.</l>
<l ln="8        ">Trichomoniasis in the bull</l>
<l ln="9        ">Was just bad luck,</l>
<l ln="10      ">All the abortions were to be expected.</l>
<l ln="11      ">The wire worm that caused a second sowing&mdash;that failed,</l>
<l ln="12      ">It happens all the time,</l>
<l ln="13      ">One learns to bear one's losses with philosophy.</l>
<l ln="14      ">After the favourite heifer died of bloat&mdash;</l>
<l ln="15      ">We sacked the cowman!</l>
<l ln="16      ">But still we had mastitis and a burnt&hyphen;out barn.</l>
<l ln="17      ">Yet the harvest was good according to the baker,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Neighbouring farms were yielding fifteen sacks to the acre</l>
<l ln="19      ">And they were simple men.</l>
<l ln="20      ">&indent;Begging for water from a wealthy see,</l>
<l ln="21      ">&indent;Crying to a steely sky for mercy,</l>
<l ln="22      ">I sold my farm to a stockbroker.</l>
<l ln="23      ">Now I have ceased to grow</l>
<l ln="24      ">I would be happier living in a city.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="19">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546827</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Snobs</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546827</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Snobs</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000015</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000015</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Snobs</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">When you asked</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">To ease a prolonged silence,</l>
<l ln="3        ">&ldquo;What would you like to be?&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="4        ">And I replied,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Being oppressed by boredom,</l>
<l ln="6        ">&ldquo;A rich man&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="7        ">You were kind enough to laugh.</l>
<l ln="8        ">But should I treat the truth</l>
<l ln="9        ">With the recklessness it deserves</l>
<l ln="10      ">And say</l>
<l ln="11      ">&ldquo;Dead&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="12      ">You would play Harrods</l>
<l ln="13      ">To my Woolworths.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546828</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>The Guns of Navarone</mainhead> <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546828</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>The Guns of Navarone</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000016</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000016</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>The Guns of Navarone</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>6Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">We sit in isolation</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The last remaining twenty in the world.</l>
<l ln="3        ">Country women waiting for a bus</l>
<l ln="4        ">A lady of the town in search of sleep</l>
<l ln="5        ">The unemployed, an old man after warmth.</l>
<l ln="6        ">We seek the reassurance of a world</l>
<l ln="7        ">More beautiful than ours, where men</l>
<l ln="8        ">Are brave or bad, handsome or unworthy.</l>
<l ln="9        ">Where morality consists of simple phrases</l>
<l ln="10      ">Taken from our childhood reading.</l>
<l ln="11      ">&ldquo;He did his duty,&rdquo; lives right to the end</l>
<l ln="12      ">Or dies a hero's death. We listen to the same thing</l>
<l ln="13      ">Every Sunday, without this colour or glory:</l>
<l ln="14      ">Without this Vistavision screen:</l>
<l ln="15      ">Without the slickness of the steel guitar</l>
<l ln="16      ">Allowed a moment to enthrall with &ldquo;Chinatown&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="17      ">The lights are dimmed. The white dressed waitress</l>
<l ln="18      ">Feels for and finds her normal face.</l>
<l ln="19      ">We start with smoke trailing behind an aircraft's belly,</l>
<pb n="20">
<l ln="20      ">A bleeding finger drawn through dear blue water.</l>
<l ln="21      ">With such dramatic skills the heroes are assembled</l>
<l ln="22      ">And set in motion for our entertainment.</l>
<l ln="23      ">The bearded guest star makes his brief appearance,</l>
<l ln="24      ">Fierce faced and aggressive in the gut.</l>
<l ln="25      ">But we are not deceived, we know this man of old,</l>
<l ln="26      ">His heart holds great compassion</l>
<l ln="27      ">For the splendid chaps he sends off to their doom.</l>
<l ln="28      ">In both our worlds the unpleasant must be done,</l>
<l ln="29      ">And sympathetic men are hard to find.</l>
<l ln="30      ">Who could wish for more than being mourned?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="31      ">Now the plot divides into different scenes.</l>
<l ln="32      ">The journey over sea, the spy, the storm.</l>
<l ln="33      ">Ship sunk upon a harsh, unfriendly shore.</l>
<l ln="34      ">Sea that storms and stuns the battered boat</l>
<l ln="35      ">Swallowing its meal in one gigantic bolt.</l>
<l ln="36      ">Only the guns and ammunition are saved,</l>
<l ln="37      ">And rightly so, for now we deal in death,</l>
<l ln="38      ">Here life has one finality, the end&mdash;</l>
<l ln="39      ">Performed with knife or gun. The camera feeds</l>
<l ln="40      ">Itself upon the spreading smear of blood.</l>
<l ln="41      ">Have pity for the belly that must bear</l>
<l ln="42      ">The defecation, gripped and twisted</l>
<l ln="43      ">By this defloration of the flower of love,</l>
<l ln="44      ">It begs to be excused. Into this turbillion</l>
<l ln="45      ">Of truth, the gentle ones are kicked with savage boot.</l>
<l ln="46      ">The toadstool lifts its crude and brutish head,</l>
<l ln="47      ">Two selves are gratified, satisfaction is all.</l>
<l ln="48      ">Surely one is sacrificed for you, my fellow watchers?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="49      ">And all the time the target. for this exercise,</l>
<l ln="50      ">The twin guns, glower over the sad sea.</l>
<l ln="51      ">Underground, beneath the mountain's crust,</l>
<l ln="52      ">They sit and stare, idle in a world of busy men.</l>
<l ln="53      ">The Mediterranean sunshine</l>
<l ln="54      ">Has not mellowed this destructive pair.</l>
<l ln="55      ">The warm air and the wine, the simple living</l>
<l ln="56      ">Cannot corrupt these intellectual giants.</l>
<pb n="21">
<l ln="57      ">Only the odour of corrupted flesh</l>
<l ln="58      ">Can end their iron interjections.</l>
<l ln="59      ">The plot unfolds, murder proliferates.</l>
<l ln="60      ">Men, throwing up their hands in praise</l>
<l ln="61      ">Or imprecation, fall like palsied puppets.</l>
<l ln="62      ">Or in slow motion slide, surprised and hurt,</l>
<l ln="63      ">Over a bridge or down a cruel cliff.</l>
<l ln="64      ">Pity the men who find no rest in mother earth,</l>
<l ln="65      ">Denied her womb for all eternity</l>
<l ln="66      ">They wash about the oceans and the seas,</l>
<l ln="67      ">Unredeemed in dissolution.</l>
<l ln="68      ">&indent;One German is allowed some human feeling.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="69      ">As it was ordained in the beginning,</l>
<l ln="70      ">The heroes breach the fort. Then starts the final scene.</l>
<l ln="71      ">The fight to fix the fuses, camouflage the plastic bombs,</l>
<l ln="72      ">Lay to view the obvious red herring&mdash;all against time.</l>
<l ln="73      ">Now the end is near the speed increases.</l>
<l ln="74      ">The fleet is seen. Five destroyers steaming for the gap.</l>
<l ln="75      ">In the hollow of our hearts we feel</l>
<l ln="76      ">The monstrous thunder of indifference,</l>
<l ln="77      ">As the two proud penises ejaculate</l>
<l ln="78      ">Their horrid semen.</l>
<l ln="79      ">Once&mdash;twice,</l>
<l ln="80      ">And then the mountain top bursts into flowers.</l>
<l ln="81      ">The whole world is transformed,</l>
<l ln="82      ">As multi&hyphen;coloured petals, stained with blood,</l>
<l ln="83      ">Float through the holocaust</l>
<l ln="84      ">Into a sea engaged in other business.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="85      ">It is enough.</l>
<l ln="86      ">A comrade's handshake, a cigarette,</l>
<l ln="87      ">A good man's love for a good woman,</l>
<l ln="88      ">And we are released into the sunshine.</l>
<l ln="89      ">&indent;Treading assuredly on the zebra crossing</l>
<l ln="90      ">&indent;We walk once more the emptiness of life.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="22">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546829</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Woman in Harrogate</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546829</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Woman in Harrogate</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000017</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000017</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Woman in Harrogate</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">She walks with a reserve</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Learnt in a husband's bed.</l>
<l ln="3        ">Her eyes take in my shabbiness</l>
<l ln="4        ">And reject me</l>
<l ln="5        ">Focusing again the empty air.</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;Breasts that cry for comfort,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Graceless dignity,</l>
<l ln="8        ">And sad respectability.</l>
<l ln="9        ">&indent;As we pass,</l>
<l ln="10      ">In a ferocity of perfume,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Sense is annihilated.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546830</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Man in Harrogate</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546830</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Man in Harrogate</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000018</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000018</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Man in Harrogate</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">So full of fire and fury</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">This tiny Jewish Griffon</l>
<l ln="3        ">His lust shoots out in slashes</l>
<l ln="4        ">From the iron that he spits on,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Seven generations of tailors have not made</l>
<l ln="6        ">This bundle of passion a lover of his trade.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="7        ">Not for you eternal moments</l>
<l ln="8        ">When inarticulate tongue</l>
<l ln="9        ">Stutters the glorious words</l>
<l ln="10      ">God sends the simple and the young,</l>
<l ln="11      ">The dream loses its clarity, the hope grows old</l>
<l ln="12      ">O cut a coat to shield you from the coming cold.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="23">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546831</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Questions Are Easy</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546831</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Questions Are Easy</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000019</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000019</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Questions Are Easy</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">The Sabbath envelopes me</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">With sad and military sounds.</l>
<l ln="3        ">An eleemosynary cat treads its way</l>
<l ln="4        ">Through the jungle of an unshorn lawn</l>
<l ln="5        ">Its ears pricked to the violence</l>
<l ln="6        ">Of my neighbour's wet and windy daughter.</l>
<l ln="7        ">I hate looking out of windows,</l>
<l ln="8        ">The broken pane, flaking paint</l>
<l ln="9        ">The squalor of my garden</l>
<l ln="10      ">Reproach the vanity of my dreams.</l>
<l ln="11      ">Upstairs my only decent suit hangs</l>
<l ln="12      ">Reserved for the working week,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Which distracts me with boredom</l>
<l ln="14      ">And leaves me shabby on Sunday,</l>
<l ln="15      ">Leaves me shabby on Sunday</l>
<l ln="16      ">And silly in a miserable household.</l>
<l ln="17      ">Two doors away the bald old man</l>
<l ln="18      ">Who won the bowlegged woman</l>
<l ln="19      ">Walls with a longer stride&mdash;</l>
<l ln="20      ">Because he wrote posterity in sperm!</l>
<l ln="21      ">Can love wear a ridiculous hat</l>
<l ln="22      ">And stand on a frosty pavement</l>
<l ln="23      ">Shivering with the lecherous stars?</l>
<l ln="24      ">Can love rise above the waistline</l>
<l ln="25      ">And still lay for eleven plus exams</l>
<l ln="26      ">At seasonal and irregular intervals?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="27      ">Questions are easy, the smallest child</l>
<l ln="28      ">Quickly learns the trick asking with serious face</l>
<l ln="29      ">&ldquo;What's that thing that hangs between the bull's legs, Mr Ashby?&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="30      ">Questions are easy.</l>
<l ln="31      ">Disconcerting dear to find I hurry home</l>
<l ln="32      ">Like any rabbit to its hole,</l>
<l ln="33      ">Though I profess contempt for how we live</l>
<l ln="34      ">And should I find you out</l>
<l ln="35      ">Feel such an emptiness and shock.</l>
<l ln="36      ">Answers are sometimes surprising.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="24">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546832</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Middle&hyphen;aged Romance</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546832</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Middle&hyphen;aged Romance</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000020</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000020</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Middle&hyphen;aged Romance</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;Admit it now, I behave like a callow boy,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Dogging your footsteps, hanging around your door,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Waiting at comers for a word or smile;</l>
<l ln="4        ">What an absurd, lugubrious figure of fun.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="5        ">This morning in the mirror, confronted by a face</l>
<l ln="6        ">Wrinkled, bleary&hyphen;eyed, teeth tart, nose all askew</l>
<l ln="7        ">I could have laughed&mdash;though the joke is an old one&mdash;</l>
<l ln="8        ">Laughed at its arrogance and coy conceit.</l>
<l ln="9        ">&ldquo;Oh ho,&rdquo; I thought, &ldquo;at it again you lecherous old bastard</l>
<l ln="10      ">You fancy once again the romantic role.</l>
<l ln="11      ">The electric shock of accidental touches,</l>
<l ln="12      ">The soft eyes on a soft night in a soft spring,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Mesmerized by hands and an untidy desiring.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="14      ">God forgive me Keats, but this is the stuff</l>
<l ln="15      ">That poems are made of in these enlightened days,</l>
<l ln="16      ">Beauty and truth is &ldquo;strictly for the birds&rdquo;.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546833</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Dead Fish</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546833</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Dead Fish</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000021</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000021</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Dead Fish</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;The swallows with their sharp neurotic cry</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Remind me the urgent hours are passing by,</l>
<l ln="3        ">A poem cannot breathe and grow</l>
<l ln="4        ">In a town that lies asleep</l>
<l ln="5        ">Where love and virtue are so cheap.&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="6        ">I could have wished that this had not been said</l>
<l ln="7        ">Her words float round my ears fish long since dead</l>
<l ln="8        ">And swill about the beaches of my mind</l>
<l ln="9        ">With all the flotsam I have left behind.</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;Her intellectual pretensions were</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;By far the least developed part of her.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="25">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546834</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Forsaken Drawing: for Betty</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546834</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Forsaken Drawing: for Betty</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000022</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000022</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Forsaken Drawing: for Betty</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">This elongated horror</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Was conceived as beauty.</l>
<l ln="3        ">A model of colour</l>
<l ln="4        ">And regal dignity.</l>
<l ln="5        ">With luck, perhaps, Mummy,</l>
<l ln="6        ">At least a Fairy Queen.</l>
<l ln="7        ">But something went awry,</l>
<l ln="8        ">The left eye, it was mean,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Had a persistent cast.</l>
<l ln="10      ">The mouth smirked with a sly</l>
<l ln="11      ">Malignancy, and past</l>
<l ln="12      ">The window a fresh start</l>
<l ln="13      ">Was offered on roller skates.</l>
<l ln="14      ">But you can't leave your heart</l>
<l ln="15      ">My love, that one equates</l>
<l ln="16      ">The I, corrects visions,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Doubts all your loves and hates,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Questions your decisions.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546835</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>A Few Lines for Old Jim, the Timekeeper</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546835</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>A Few Lines for Old Jim, the Timekeeper</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000023</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000023</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Few Lines for Old Jim, the Timekeeper</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Last night, card clocked and ready for cleansing</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">From the day's dullness; passing our ritual joke</l>
<l ln="3        ">About a smell of snow in the air, you</l>
<l ln="4        ">My late puppet&hyphen;master uttered your last words.</l>
<l ln="5        ">&ldquo;Another quarter and I'll be up the road.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="6        ">Well Jim, time was passing quicker than dinner hour</l>
<l ln="7        ">And you ran out of road. The warning bell</l>
<l ln="8        ">Ended your dreams of tomorrow, the final whistle blew,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Who but a tiny handful gave two hoots?</l>
<l ln="10      ">The clock still ticks, the hooter blows its great Amen,</l>
<l ln="11      ">But you, old sharer of our sorrows, can lie in late.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="26">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546836</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>My Poor Darling</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546836</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>My Poor Darling</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000024</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000024</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>My Poor Darling</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">My poor dear</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Sitting here,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Dreaming,</l>
<l ln="4        ">In an old coat,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Before the freshly lit fire.</l>
<l ln="6        ">Before dawn</l>
<l ln="7        ">Is quite born,</l>
<l ln="8        ">And night snuffed his candle</l>
<l ln="9        ">And dog end of desire.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="10      ">My poor dear</l>
<l ln="11      ">Sitting here,</l>
<l ln="12      ">&ldquo;Stale Every Morning&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="13      ">The aspirin and hot tea,</l>
<l ln="14      ">If only!</l>
<l ln="15      ">I'm lonely!</l>
<l ln="16      ">Burnt shame and hard boiled pride</l>
<l ln="17      ">And the eternal me.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="18      ">My poor dear</l>
<l ln="19      ">Sitting here,</l>
<l ln="20      ">If we pray&mdash;forgive us</l>
<l ln="21      ">Could, would our dull hearts sing</l>
<l ln="22      ">Like the bird</l>
<l ln="23      ">That we heard</l>
<l ln="24      ">Twenty years ago this spring.</l>
<l ln="25      ">&indent;O my poor darling!</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546837</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Love Poem</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546837</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Love Poem</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000025</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000025</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Love Poem</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">She with a beauty still unblemished.</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Time they say has been unkind,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Her eyes swim in a sea of sorrow</l>
<l ln="4        ">Her skin hangs on an old shame,</l>
<l ln="5        ">They are pleased with their sense of pity.</l>
<pb n="27">
<l ln="6        ">&indent;This morning, with a flat face,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Breakfasting on a Beethoven Sonata</l>
<l ln="8        ">Giving your mind to madness</l>
<l ln="9        ">You pursued a non&hyphen;existent argument</l>
<l ln="10      ">To an irrefutable end.</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;Outside, the sun sparkled on wet grass</l>
<l ln="12      ">Splashed with light the apple blossom,</l>
<l ln="13      ">A stupid tree cried, &ldquo;God be praised!&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="14      ">You looked into your yawning hell and wept.</l>
<l ln="15      ">I have no pity left to put into your hand,</l>
<l ln="16      ">The bare skin shows beneath the hair of love.</l>
<l ln="17      ">But should I find enough</l>
<l ln="18      ">To take your thin, tired throat between my hands</l>
<l ln="19      ">And squeeze the breath of death into your form,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Out of the agony of an eye</l>
<l ln="21      ">Filled with dreadful accusations</l>
<l ln="22      ">You would weep,</l>
<l ln="23      ">&indent;&ldquo;This, my love, when life is sweet!&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546838</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Attempted Suicide</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546838</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Attempted Suicide</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000026</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000026</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Attempted Suicide</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I have laboured in your vineyard twenty years,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Squeezing the grapes of love until what's left</l>
<l ln="3        ">Is sludge and sediment.</l>
<l ln="4        ">The vats are empty though we both still tread</l>
<l ln="5        ">With desperate feet the fruitless skins of love.</l>
<l ln="6        ">The heart is numb with serf inflicted wounds,</l>
<l ln="7        ">The body falls which ever way it fancies.</l>
<l ln="8        ">As the salt and spittle bubble on your lips</l>
<l ln="9        ">I am consumed in an involuntary yawn.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="28">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546839</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Cuckoo</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546839</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Cuckoo</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000027</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000027</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Cuckoo</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">He looked with intermediate eyes</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Along the lineaments of her thighs.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="3        ">Man's history was just a fleeting</l>
<l ln="4        ">Moment that led to this lovers' meeting.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="5        ">Standing around incurious cows</l>
<l ln="6        ">Watch importunate hands invade her blouse.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="7        ">The limpid air is bean blossom sweet</l>
<l ln="8        ">And her sunlit hair is a field of wheat.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">The minor animal creation</l>
<l ln="10      ">Ignore this momentous copulation.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="11      ">A cuckoo whistles its ribald sound</l>
<l ln="12      ">To the lovers stretched on the stony ground.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546840</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Marriage</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546840</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Marriage</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000028</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000028</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Marriage</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Marriage held together</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">In the warmer weather</l>
<l ln="3        ">By cold social duress,</l>
<l ln="4        ">God finds it hard to bless.</l>
<l ln="5        ">There is no joy for me</l>
<l ln="6        ">Or you that I can see</l>
<l ln="7        ">In burning all our boats,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Cutting each other's throats,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Yet share out all the blame</l>
<l ln="10      ">The shame is still the same.</l>
<l ln="11      ">Under a field of stars</l>
<l ln="12      ">Why is it only Mars</l>
<l ln="13      ">Comes up with an answer,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Where is my own Cancer?</l>
<pb n="29">
<l ln="15      ">However much the head</l>
<l ln="16      ">May justify the bed,</l>
<l ln="17      ">The lymph between the thigh</l>
<l ln="18      ">Increase and fructify,</l>
<l ln="19      ">At some time one must start</l>
<l ln="20      ">To celebrate the heart.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546841</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>For Suki Dara</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546841</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>For Suki Dara</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000029</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000029</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>For Suki Dara</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">You sit and survey your jolly kittens</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">As they dart about like minnows on the floor.</l>
<l ln="3        ">Unconcerned with naughtiness, you tolerate</l>
<l ln="4        ">Their mischief, ignore their breaches of good taste</l>
<l ln="5        ">Until they nip your nipples or use their claws</l>
<l ln="6        ">With more vigour than discretion</l>
<l ln="7        ">Then you deal them an uncompromising swipe</l>
<l ln="8        ">That allows no misunderstanding of your position.</l>
<l ln="9        ">Yet we had begun to fear the stars</l>
<l ln="10      ">The time and the right Tom would never be in conjunction.</l>
<l ln="11      ">Always that useless Ginger sod hanging around</l>
<l ln="12      ">Never seemed to have the tool to finish the job.</l>
<l ln="13      ">Yet what he lacked in potency</l>
<l ln="14      ">He made up for in persistency</l>
<l ln="15      ">Ploughing through snow and frost, to rendezvous</l>
<l ln="16      ">With you on the kitchen window sill.</l>
<l ln="17      ">His habits there left much to be desired</l>
<l ln="18      ">But the children fell for his wistful devotion line.</l>
<l ln="19      ">&indent;Old black Tom called just once</l>
<l ln="20      ">&indent;There was no need to call again.</l>
<l ln="21      ">&indent;Moral,&mdash;Love is pierc&eacute;d hearts on walls</l>
<l ln="22      ">&indent;&indent;But romance is a load of balls.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="30">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546842</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>In the City</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546842</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>In the City</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000030</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000030</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>In the City</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Now, before I know you,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">While the eye is uncertain</l>
<l ln="3        ">And the eradicable warmth</l>
<l ln="4        ">Permits a pleasure in your face.</l>
<l ln="5        ">Now, while the blood</l>
<l ln="6        ">Makes its extravagant promise</l>
<l ln="7        ">The residual fires</l>
<l ln="8        ">Express a mild desire,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Let us predict the predictable</l>
<l ln="10      ">Chart the vulgarity of experience.</l>
<l ln="11      ">We could meet in a city</l>
<l ln="12      ">Which would not pass judgement.</l>
<l ln="13      ">In the amoral streets&mdash;</l>
<l ln="14      ">Guts held in a clenched fist&mdash;</l>
<l ln="15      ">Suffer the ache for knowledge.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="16      ">&indent;And should we learn from this,</l>
<l ln="17      ">This worried insemination?</l>
<l ln="18      ">Should we, when what comes between us</l>
<l ln="19      ">Resumes its languid posture,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Know the truth of one another?</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546843</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>In the Strict Sense</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546843</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>In the Strict Sense</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000031</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000031</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>In the Strict Sense</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">In the strict sense of a strict word, poetry,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">This hardly is a poem.</l>
<l ln="3        ">It has no formal shape</l>
<l ln="4        ">No subtle rhythm, no discipline in fact.</l>
<l ln="5        ">It is the reflection of a reflex action,</l>
<l ln="6        ">An attempt to describe the complexities</l>
<l ln="7        ">Of a relationship outside the accepted code.</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;You will agree, I know, that externally at least</l>
<l ln="9        ">Meeting in a rather squalid room</l>
<l ln="10      ">Presided over by a British Railway urn</l>
<l ln="11      ">Is not conducive to the wilder passions.</l>
<pb n="31">
<l ln="12      ">The whole point is however that we meet</l>
<l ln="13      ">And by this simple act of innocence</l>
<l ln="14      ">Become involved in conflicts</l>
<l ln="15      ">That tear the heart in two.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="16      ">&indent;Tonight I was late again!</l>
<l ln="17      ">Saw you from across the track</l>
<l ln="18      ">And found my feet taking the steps</l>
<l ln="19      ">Two at a time.</l>
<l ln="20      ">Felt pretty bad about this;</l>
<l ln="21      ">To see you desperately feigning interest</l>
<l ln="22      ">In notice board and indicator</l>
<l ln="23      ">Filled me with sorrow and despair.</l>
<l ln="24      ">I have become so stupid I forget</l>
<l ln="25      ">The simple acts of common thoughtfulness.</l>
<l ln="26      ">Forgive me.</l>
<l ln="27      ">&indent;One certainty in an ever changing world</l>
<l ln="28      ">Is the battle for a table and two chairs,</l>
<l ln="29      ">That and the indifference of the coffee&mdash;</l>
<l ln="30      ">Which I never seem to taste.</l>
<l ln="31      ">Tonight you have remembered your father's paper</l>
<l ln="32      ">Having all the virtues of a dutiful daughter.</l>
<l ln="33      ">I wish I could forget the sullen clock,</l>
<l ln="34      ">The bus, the crowds that jostle at our shoulders.</l>
<l ln="35      ">Never get the time somehow</l>
<l ln="36      ">To ask you all the questions</l>
<l ln="37      ">That chase around my lonely mind at midnight.</l>
<l ln="38      ">About the other time you were engaged,</l>
<l ln="39      ">What happened, where was it and how long ago?</l>
<l ln="40      ">You realize by now I'm very nosey.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="41      ">&indent;You are such a normal person</l>
<l ln="42      ">I cling to your commonsense</l>
<l ln="43      ">Making demands that are no doubt unfair.</l>
<l ln="44      ">Do I then use you for my own ends?</l>
<l ln="45      ">Are you too kind to say the benediction</l>
<l ln="46      ">To an affair with no apparent future?</l>
<l ln="47      ">Do I offend against one of God's little ones?</l>
<pb n="32">
<l ln="48      ">&indent;Enough,</l>
<l ln="49      ">The time is twelve,</l>
<l ln="50      ">The children are asleep,</l>
<l ln="51      ">Tomorrow has his foot firm in the door.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546844</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Roundhay Park: for Joyce</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546844</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Roundhay Park: for Joyce</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000032</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000032</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Roundhay Park: for Joyce</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Snatching an illicit hour together</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Happy to be anywhere at all</l>
<l ln="3        ">We look, eyes soft with love,</l>
<l ln="4        ">At the washed out roses.</l>
<l ln="5        ">&ldquo;This&rdquo; you say, pointing</l>
<l ln="6        ">A tarnished bud, &ldquo;is Peace.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="7        ">And this is true, for peace</l>
<l ln="8        ">Is always threatened at the edges</l>
<l ln="9        ">By a headache and tomorrow</l>
<l ln="10      ">Or a quick touch of hands</l>
<l ln="11      ">A muttered goodbye, a wave</l>
<l ln="12      ">And a bus disappearing in the dusk.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546845</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Poetry</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546845</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Poetry</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000033</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000033</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Poetry</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Poetry is not making up stories</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">With pretty phrases and happy endings.</l>
<l ln="3        ">It does not seek to show a world</l>
<l ln="4        ">Of beautiful beasts</l>
<l ln="5        ">Serenely strolling through pleasant pastures;</l>
<l ln="6        ">It does not seek to show cool reason</l>
<l ln="7        ">Dominating the human situation,</l>
<l ln="8        ">How could it?</l>
<l ln="9        ">In fact there is so little left</l>
<l ln="10      ">To write a poem about these days</l>
<l ln="11      ">That I can visualise a time,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Not too far distant,</l>
<pb n="33">
<l ln="13      ">When the breed becomes extinct.</l>
<l ln="14      ">Take the spring or last winter (any offers?)</l>
<l ln="15      ">Take birth and death</l>
<l ln="16      ">And the ever popular copulation,</l>
<l ln="17      ">They have all been done,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Done to death.</l>
<l ln="19      ">Or again, pike are popular</l>
<l ln="20      ">And all the tiny creatures</l>
<l ln="21      ">At the bottom of my garden,</l>
<l ln="22      ">Flies and frogs, even compost heaps</l>
<l ln="23      ">Have had their moment of glory.</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;But now the fishermen and DDT</l>
<l ln="25      ">Are building a new and better world.</l>
<l ln="26      ">All that remains amiss</l>
<l ln="27      ">Is that old reprobate the human heart,</l>
<l ln="28      ">And even that they tell me is coming along nicely.</l>
<l ln="29      ">Anytime now an anti&hyphen;guilt pill is expected</l>
<l ln="30      ">Which will alter for all time</l>
<l ln="31      ">The whole nature of the poem.</l>
<l ln="32      ">Then we can expect the modern Lawrence to write</l>
<l ln="33      ">&ldquo;Glory is of the camshaft</l>
<l ln="34      ">And down its magnificent nuts and pinions.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="35      ">When the great day comes</l>
<l ln="36      ">Who knows, Jesus might merely be an oilcan.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546846</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>What You Are</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546846</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>What You Are</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000034</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000034</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>What You Are</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">What you are, you are, so don't complain</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">A twig that twitches over water</l>
<l ln="3        ">A figure seen upon a screen</l>
<l ln="4        ">And worn for half an hour</l>
<l ln="5        ">Or sometimes, not so often, what you see</l>
<l ln="6        ">My eyes say, what they think you ought to be.</l>
<l ln="7        ">And for the rest, standing under God's rain</l>
<l ln="8        ">A conscious being, awkward, dull and plain.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="34">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546847</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Budgerigar</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546847</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Budgerigar</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000035</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000035</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Budgerigar</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">How like the human type you are my pretty bird,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">You speak but what you say are words that you have heard,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Shouted or cooed into your ear until you find,</l>
<l ln="4        ">They slither off your tongue, but never reach your mind.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546848</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Sunday Morning Lie&hyphen;in</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546848</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Sunday Morning Lie&hyphen;in</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000036</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000036</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Sunday Morning Lie&hyphen;in</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;What is the matter?&rdquo; you said</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Turning a tired head</l>
<l ln="3        ">On a dishevelled sheet,</l>
<l ln="4        ">The question was indiscreet.</l>
<l ln="5        ">To temporize I asked you &ldquo;why&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="6        ">Unaware that you had heard me sigh,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Surprised my tiny exhalation</l>
<l ln="8        ">Should cause you more than irritation,</l>
<l ln="9        ">How could I say &ldquo;I wish that you were dead&rdquo;?</l>
<l ln="10      ">This is the sin that holds the heart in fee</l>
<l ln="11      ">For every hurt one tries to make amends</l>
<l ln="12      ">After all, we had been more than friends,</l>
<l ln="13      ">I stumble down and make a pot of tea.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546849</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>The State of the Union</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546849</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>The State of the Union</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000037</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000037</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>The State of the Union</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">She</speaker>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;&ldquo;I never intended&mdash;</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">We were such good friends!&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">He</speaker>
<l ln="3        ">&indent;&ldquo;What is said is not intended</l>
<l ln="4        ">To have precise meaning</l>
<l ln="5        ">Or to be believed.</l>
<l ln="6        ">What the eyes reveal</l>
<pb n="35">
<l ln="7        ">Or the breasts suggest</l>
<l ln="8        ">Finds an ache in me.</l>
<l ln="9        ">Given a suitable night,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Warm, a traditional moon,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Reflection only on the lake,</l>
<l ln="12      ">After the fingers find the nipple</l>
<l ln="13      ">In the gentler preliminaries</l>
<l ln="14      ">The legs automatically open!&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><speaker r="italic">She</speaker>
<l ln="15      ">&indent;&ldquo;A relationship between</l>
<l ln="16      ">Two differently constructed bodies</l>
<l ln="17      ">Always ends ...&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546850</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Fingers</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546850</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Fingers</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000038</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000038</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Fingers</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Fingers can poke and pluck</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Can pinch and prod,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Cleanse the nose and soul</l>
<l ln="4        ">Of dirt and sin.</l>
<l ln="5        ">Fingers can lie white worms</l>
<l ln="6        ">Upon a velvet couch.</l>
<l ln="7        ">Fingers can fumble in a feverish frenzy</l>
<l ln="8        ">Where the censor's mind</l>
<l ln="9        ">Would hesitate to enter.</l>
<l ln="10      ">The common view is that the mind</l>
<l ln="11      ">Controls the movement of these five,</l>
<l ln="12      ">This is, of course, not true,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Or looking at them now</l>
<l ln="14      ">I am all evil.</l>
<l ln="15      ">If I take a cleaver</l>
<l ln="16      ">And with a dean, quick stroke</l>
<l ln="17      ">Sever them at the knuckle</l>
<l ln="18      ">To lie five bleeding stumps</l>
<l ln="19      ">Upon the table,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Is my offence removed?</l>
<l ln="21      ">She has two hands that tear my heart in two.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="36">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546851</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>A Tiny Scar?</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546851</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>A Tiny Scar?</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000039</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000039</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Tiny Scar?</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Love is a thorn and can catch</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Grasping fingers when they snatch</l>
<l ln="3        ">To claim the chosen rose.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="4        ">Love is only understood</l>
<l ln="5        ">When a ragged smear of blood</l>
<l ln="6        ">Her rigid terms impose.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="7        ">Rose and thorn, a tiny scar,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Show my darling just how far</l>
<l ln="9        ">We have come to where we are.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546852</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>And They Came to a City</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546852</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>And They Came to a City</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000040</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000040</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>And They Came to a City</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Ironic one should find the seeds</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of any sort of love in Leeds,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Or feel the heart exposed to pain</l>
<l ln="4        ">In areas round Vicar Lane,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Where I remember as a youth</l>
<l ln="6        ">The flesh becoming quite uncouth,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Pressed in the doorways of cheap shops</l>
<l ln="8        ">Hands confused with buttons and pops.</l>
<l ln="9        ">For it was hard at seventeen</l>
<l ln="10      ">To find oneself caught in between</l>
<l ln="11      ">Two wars, living in a city</l>
<l ln="12      ">One could neither love nor pity.</l>
<l ln="13      ">So this clandestine pilgrimage</l>
<l ln="14      ">In what is called maturer age</l>
<l ln="15      ">Holds undertones of problems we</l>
<l ln="16      ">Did not find answered by Paul Klee,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Or local intellectual scribes</l>
<l ln="18      ">With vitriolic diatribes.</l>
<l ln="19      ">One must assume that no one man</l>
<l ln="20      ">Can milk the stars into a can,</l>
<pb n="37">
<l ln="21      ">Or place his finger on the spot</l>
<l ln="22      ">That's troubled him from the year dot.</l>
<l ln="23      ">When love sets up its row of fences</l>
<l ln="24      ">Jump and damn the consequences</l>
<l ln="25      ">Or so one mutters to oneself</l>
<l ln="26      ">Prostrate upon a mattressed shelf.</l>
<l ln="27      ">Life shows two roads and one must choose,</l>
<l ln="28      ">Whichever one you take you lose</l>
<l ln="29      ">Some virtue from your meagre stock,</l>
<l ln="30      ">For one cannot turn back the clock</l>
<l ln="31      ">Redeeming all one's indiscretion</l>
<l ln="32      ">With a show of self&hyphen;confession.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="33      ">Into your neat, well&hyphen;ordered life</l>
<l ln="34      ">I bring four children and a wife</l>
<l ln="35      ">A begging bowl and a carving knife.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546853</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>A Poem about Not Writing a Poem</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546853</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>A Poem about Not Writing a Poem</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000041</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000041</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Poem about Not Writing a Poem</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I could, if pressed, write I suppose</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">About the beauty of your nose</l>
<l ln="3        ">Although the truth is&mdash;dare I tell?&mdash;</l>
<l ln="4        ">I don't recall it very well.</l>
<l ln="5        ">Your eyes would make some copy too</l>
<l ln="6        ">I do remember both are blue</l>
<l ln="7        ">And mellow like a well&hyphen;kept wine</l>
<l ln="8        ">So much superior to mine</l>
<l ln="9        ">Which have a rather shifty roll</l>
<l ln="10      ">Like two fish swimming in a bowl.</l>
<l ln="11      ">Your ears I will assume are there</l>
<l ln="12      ">Incarcerated in your hair.</l>
<l ln="13      ">I should, because it's fair and just,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Describe the merits of your bust,</l>
<l ln="15      ">But this might give the verse a twist</l>
<l ln="16      ">Repugnant to the Methodist.</l>
<l ln="17      ">Therefore between your neck and feet</l>
<l ln="18      ">I shall be moral and discreet,</l>
<pb n="38">
<l ln="19      ">I'll not remark your charming grin</l>
<l ln="20      ">Is there a hint of double chin?</l>
<l ln="21      ">Perish the thought, the man's a beast</l>
<l ln="22      ">Who when confronted with a feast</l>
<l ln="23      ">That's perfect to its seventh course</l>
<l ln="24      ">Would quibble at the brandy sauce.</l>
<l ln="25      ">Your hands still give me quite a fright</l>
<l ln="26      ">They look so helpless, cold and white</l>
<l ln="27      ">I'd worry if you didn't take care</l>
<l ln="28      ">To wrap up in the cold night air,</l>
<l ln="29      ">Or if your tongue when in full spate</l>
<l ln="30      ">Forgot the last time that you ate!</l>
<l ln="31      ">But since I am yours to command</l>
<l ln="32      ">I'll discipline this errant hand</l>
<l ln="33      ">Before it gets quite carried away</l>
<l ln="34      ">And mentions things it shouldn't say.</l>
<l ln="35      ">From me no moral dereliction</l>
<l ln="36      ">To titillate the &ldquo;women's section&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="37      ">No Eve, no Adam and no fall</l>
<l ln="38      ">In fact I'll write no poem at all.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546854</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>At the Right Time</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546854</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>At the Right Time</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000042</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000042</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>At the Right Time</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Never believe the day will fall</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Exactly as you want it to.</l>
<l ln="3        ">Imperfections start with the child</l>
<l ln="4        ">Disciplined upon its pot</l>
<l ln="5        ">When sun and sounds insist</l>
<l ln="6        ">That joy is waiting</l>
<l ln="7        ">In playroom or green garden.</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;So all through life the event</l>
<l ln="9        ">Is never timed to meet the need.</l>
<l ln="10      ">And love is no exception to the rule,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Makes an oasis in a happy desert,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Agitates the womb, asks, and sometimes gets,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Impossible feats of endurance.</l>
<pb n="39">
<l ln="14      ">&indent;If love has laid its finger on your heart</l>
<l ln="15      ">Take it&mdash;or travel to a far country.</l>
<l ln="16      ">Whichever way you'll find the fever burn</l>
<l ln="17      ">As sure as night will find you twist and turn.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546855</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>O Do Not Speak</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546855</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>O Do Not Speak</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000043</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000043</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>O Do Not Speak</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;O do not speak</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Do not say a word.</l>
<l ln="3        ">Day breaks with glass on stone,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Fingers fumbling for yesterday's pain,</l>
<l ln="5        ">The familiar bitterness of living.</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;But now, while your eyes still hold</l>
<l ln="7        ">A certain integrity,</l>
<l ln="8        ">In this fragile peace</l>
<l ln="9        ">Set in a hostile soil,</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;Do not speak</l>
<l ln="11      ">O do not say a word.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546856</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>A Cold Wind</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546856</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>A Cold Wind</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000044</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000044</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Cold Wind</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I have seen your face all week;</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Following with my eyes in streets and stores</l>
<l ln="3        ">The most unlikely strangers.</l>
<l ln="4        ">And though I told myself</l>
<l ln="5        ">&ldquo;Don't be a fool&rdquo;, the hope persisted.</l>
<l ln="6        ">Today, on your return</l>
<l ln="7        ">I scuttle rabbit&hyphen;like from work</l>
<l ln="8        ">To find your bus has gone!</l>
<l ln="9        ">&indent;Suddenly, no one is like you,</l>
<l ln="10      ">The street is filled with faces dull and sullen,</l>
<l ln="11      ">From the east a cold wind blows.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="40">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546857</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Lovers</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546857</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Lovers</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000045</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000045</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Lovers</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;Do you love me?&rdquo;</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Sooner or later the question must be asked,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Or smouldering in some comer of the mind</l>
<l ln="4        ">It grows to such a pitch of feverish doubt</l>
<l ln="5        ">The mind itself is burnt up by the flame.</l>
<l ln="6        ">So out it comes,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Whispered over the coffee cups</l>
<l ln="8        ">Or teasingly while shivering in the cold.</l>
<l ln="9        ">&indent;The answer hardly ever satisfies,</l>
<l ln="10      ">&ldquo;Sometimes: not now: yesterday&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="11      ">And with private reservations one says &ldquo;yes&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="12      ">So though I know that words are only words,</l>
<l ln="13      ">And what your true eyes tell me must be true,</l>
<l ln="14      ">&ldquo;Darling, do you love me?&rdquo;</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546858</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Come O Lord</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546858</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Come O Lord</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000046</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000046</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Come O Lord</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Come like winter sunshine</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Or the Christmas rose,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Come as frost on the lawn</l>
<l ln="4        ">Or the dancer's pose.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="5        ">Come as sudden death</l>
<l ln="6        ">Or as a turning head,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Come as shyly as sleep</l>
<l ln="8        ">When words have been said.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">Come as sorrow to joy,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Like a daughter's smile</l>
<l ln="11      ">Or come with the warmth</l>
<l ln="12      ">Of a lover's profile.</l></pdiv>
<pb n="41">
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">Come as rain, come as sleet,</l>
<l ln="14      ">A smile in the street,</l>
<l ln="15      ">Come as noise or silence,</l>
<l ln="16      ">Come as peace or violence,</l>
<l ln="17      ">But come Lord come.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546859</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Down&mdash;by the Old Millbank</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546859</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Down&mdash;by the Old Millbank</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000047</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000047</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Down&mdash;by the Old Millbank</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Sunlight on the Thames</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Has its own particular virtue.</l>
<l ln="3        ">The buildings like decaying shark's teeth,</l>
<l ln="4        ">The Lowry figures, walking on awakening grass,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Placate the critical eye.</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;If life was as innocent as a springtime afternoon,</l>
<l ln="7        ">And yesterday's anger left the veins unpunctured.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="8        ">&indent;O fragile happiness</l>
<l ln="9        ">That shatters at the impact of a shadow,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Making me tread with unaccustomed care</l>
<l ln="11      ">Around the fragments of a harsh experience.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546860</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Reductions</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546860</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Reductions</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000048</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000048</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Reductions</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">The conversations of minor civil servants</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Are tedious and very long;</l>
<l ln="3        ">What one does with begonias,</l>
<l ln="4        ">The proper way to lay a concrete path,</l>
<l ln="5        ">The stupidity of the unemployed.</l>
<l ln="6        ">One smokes a cigarette,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Feels embarrassed and foolish;</l>
<l ln="8        ">Ignorant of the answers to</l>
<l ln="9        ">Everyday problems of ordinary life.</l>
<l ln="10      ">After robbing the taxpayers</l>
<l ln="11      ">Of five minutes' official teabreak,</l>
<pb n="42">
<l ln="12      ">One returns to the counter to find</l>
<l ln="13      ">Mr O'Flaherty bibulous and broke,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Whispering for &ldquo;a wee loan&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="15      ">To ring his sick mother in Watford.</l>
<l ln="16      ">&ldquo;Dance me a jig, Mr O'Flaherty,</l>
<l ln="17      ">While I whistle an Irish tune.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="18      ">&ldquo;With pleasure&rdquo; says Mr O.,</l>
<l ln="19      ">And his thin legs dance to my weak whistle.</l>
<l ln="20      ">Suddenly over my shoulder appears</l>
<l ln="21      ">The supervisor's face, code heavy,</l>
<l ln="22      ">Scored through with amendments.</l>
<l ln="23      ">The weak whistle diminishes</l>
<l ln="24      ">To sibilance and silence,</l>
<l ln="25      ">The rheumatic legs stop twitching</l>
<l ln="26      ">My pencil becomes formal and inhuman.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546861</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>A Few Lines for Mother</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546861</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>A Few Lines for Mother</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000049</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000049</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Few Lines for Mother</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">A stern lady with a huge hooked nose</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Who limped through life one foot set firm in Heaven.</l>
<l ln="3        ">How Grandad put the leaven in her loins</l>
<l ln="4        ">Was not revealed within the <hi r="italic">Joyful News,</hi></l>
<l ln="5        ">But you, my mother, blessed the sacrifice.</l>
<l ln="6        ">For you it seemed so easy to be good</l>
<l ln="7        ">Locked in a close&hyphen;knit nonconformist world,</l>
<l ln="8        ">But when I shed my soft and shallow sins</l>
<l ln="9        ">I felt no guilt before the eyes of God</l>
<l ln="10      ">But found your sorrow more than I could bear,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Lying in bed in terror at the thought</l>
<l ln="12      ">That you might die and leave me all alone.</l>
<l ln="13      ">&ldquo;Too close for comfort&rdquo;, now the rebel cut</l>
<l ln="14      ">With one sharp stroke the last remaining cord</l>
<l ln="15      ">Leaving his mother's house not to return.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="16      ">&indent;My first true love so thwarted in your plan,</l>
<l ln="17      ">&indent;Forgive God, if you can, the sins of man.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="43">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546862</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>London</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546862</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>London</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000050</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000050</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>London</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">There is little in this frenzy</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">That concerns the human heart</l>
<l ln="3        ">And the daily Crucifixion</l>
<l ln="4        ">Can be the only thing worth living for.</l>
<l ln="5        ">&indent;Inserted in a tube and shot</l>
<l ln="6        ">Like shit into the sea</l>
<l ln="7        ">One enters the city and sinks</l>
<l ln="8        ">Into obscurity, or finds,</l>
<l ln="9        ">If vested with morality,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Scope for such eccentricities</l>
<l ln="11      ">As writing verse, or</l>
<l ln="12      ">Calling toil a form of service.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">Returning each night upon the tide</l>
<l ln="14      ">To desolate suburbs</l>
<l ln="15      ">Where love dribbles away</l>
<l ln="16      ">In loneliness in pubs,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Staring at inert hands</l>
<l ln="18      ">Through alcohol dulled senses.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546863</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Legs by Dictionary Definition</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546863</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Legs by Dictionary Definition</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000051</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000051</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Legs by Dictionary Definition</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;Toes&rdquo;, an alliterative ten, overlapping,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Screwed tight during the tossed away</l>
<l ln="3        ">Hours of a thoughtless night.</l>
<l ln="4        ">&ldquo;Toes&rdquo;, &ldquo;trodden on&rdquo;, or &ldquo;on which to tread&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="5        ">But they &ldquo;never toe the line&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;The &ldquo;instep&rdquo;, which is always &ldquo;falling&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="7        ">From Grace, &ldquo;out of step&rdquo; with society,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Never springing to attention when</l>
<l ln="9        ">The forelock needs a tug.</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;&ldquo;Heel&rdquo;, which when in love last year</l>
<l ln="11      ">I was &ldquo;head over&rdquo;, and &ldquo;behaved like&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="12      ">&ldquo;A vulnerable part&rdquo;, I am often</l>
<l ln="13      ">&ldquo;Down at&rdquo;, &ldquo;come to&rdquo;, or on occasions &ldquo;cool&rdquo;.</l>
<pb n="44">
<l ln="14      ">When the times get tough</l>
<l ln="15      ">I show &ldquo;a clean pair of&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;&ldquo;Ankle&rdquo;, a rum joint where I have been &ldquo;twisted&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="17      ">&ldquo;Sprained&rdquo;, &ldquo;strained&rdquo;, and &ldquo;fettered&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="18      ">At times has &ldquo;good connections&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="19      ">&indent;&ldquo;Knee&rdquo;, and &ldquo;thigh&rdquo;, which is you and I</l>
<l ln="20      ">Or grammatically, you and me,</l>
<l ln="21      ">&ldquo;Bony&rdquo;, yet &ldquo;easily bruised&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="22      ">&ldquo;Soft&rdquo;, and &ldquo;occasioned to cramp&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="23      ">Which my hand impulsively reaches for.</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;&ldquo;Knees&rdquo;, which still refuse to kneel</l>
<l ln="25      ">To One whose feet I am unworthy ...</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546864</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Ask a Silly Question</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546864</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Ask a Silly Question</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000052</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000052</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Ask a Silly Question</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I have been unwell for some time,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Since the magnolias blossomed,</l>
<l ln="3        ">And now the hay harvest is over</l>
<l ln="4        ">Combines consume the cornfields.</l>
<l ln="5        ">&indent;Being unable to decide</l>
<l ln="6        ">The simplest details of living</l>
<l ln="7        ">What to have for lunch,</l>
<l ln="8        ">When or where to marry.</l>
<l ln="9        ">Having annoyed my friends with tactless letters</l>
<l ln="10      ">And lost the knack of writing poems,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Nothing remains, for the religious man, but prayer.</l>
<l ln="12      ">So I have bombarded the Lord</l>
<l ln="13      ">With pleas for mercy and guidance, without result,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Until this morning when, asking</l>
<l ln="15      ">&ldquo;Lord what shall I do?&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="16      ">The answer came&mdash;GO TO DUNSTABLE!</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="45">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546865</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Never</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546865</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Never</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000053</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000053</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Never</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">The footsteps that are never yours,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Knock upon the door never you,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Never the letter where my feet are wiped.</l>
<l ln="4        ">The red coat never wrapped around</l>
<l ln="5        ">Your never violated body.</l>
<l ln="6        ">The telephone number never forgotten.</l>
<l ln="7        ">My never revealed excursions</l>
<l ln="8        ">Never suspected by my ever loving.</l>
<l ln="9        ">The man who was never me</l>
<l ln="10      ">Never loved by the never loving</l>
<l ln="11      ">Woman who was never you,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Never being more than my imagination,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Which day after day never forgets</l>
<l ln="14      ">Your never developed breasts, and sighs</l>
<l ln="15      ">For the consummation of a never intended affair.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546866</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Tidal Waves</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546866</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Tidal Waves</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000054</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000054</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Tidal Waves</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Being in a moral sense old&hyphen;fashioned</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The similes I use will not confuse you,</l>
<l ln="3        ">The earth and moon. Like us</l>
<l ln="4        ">Two disparate bodies seeking similarities.</l>
<l ln="5        ">Without will and unable to resist</l>
<l ln="6        ">You draw my tides and leave my sand exposed</l>
<l ln="7        ">To waste and sun, the foot of man and bird.</l>
<l ln="8        ">I send exploratory rockets to your atmosphere</l>
<l ln="9        ">Seeking a landing on your foolish heart,</l>
<l ln="10      ">And find there that the mechanism of love</l>
<l ln="11      ">Shatters upon the edges of your rocky mind.</l>
<l ln="12      ">Or should I, by scientific expertise,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Succeed in circling you and bring</l>
<l ln="14      ">My missile back to its home base,</l>
<l ln="15      ">It comes back as a singing bird or thunder.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="46">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546867</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>The Arthritic Tree on Otley Bridge</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546867</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>The Arthritic Tree on Otley Bridge</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000055</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000055</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>The Arthritic Tree on Otley Bridge</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">In Otley, the arthritic tree,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The first time that you went with me,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Was naked to the winter's waste</l>
<l ln="4        ">And too distorted for your taste.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="5        ">The bridge stepped over in one span</l>
<l ln="6        ">No longer than the life of man,</l>
<l ln="7        ">And on its farther bank there stood</l>
<l ln="8        ">Man's sin portrayed in tortured wood.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">&indent;Its fearful shape disturbs my mind</l>
<l ln="10      ">Though twelve fine summers lie behind.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200546868</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead><hi r="italic">Poem</hi> [I say this will pass in a day]</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546868</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Poem [I say this will pass in a day]</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000056</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000056</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Poem [I say this will pass in a day]</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I say this will pass in a day</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And tomorrow feel the same way.</l>
<l ln="3        ">Or the pain will die in a week</l>
<l ln="4        ">Yet the tears still run down my cheek,</l>
<l ln="5        ">And seem like to be there</l>
<l ln="6        ">Until the end of the year.</l>
<l ln="7        ">Yet a relief to find</l>
<l ln="8        ">I still retain an analytical mind</l>
<l ln="9        ">And with a little effort can take apart</l>
<l ln="10      ">Your head, untouched vagina and your heart.</l>
<l ln="11      ">If I may say, and cause you no offence</l>
<l ln="12      ">My first impression was your innocence</l>
<l ln="13      ">And to be frank I felt a certain pity</l>
<l ln="14      ">For your self&hyphen;evident inadequacy.</l>
<l ln="15      ">Your eyes showed worry, mouth was most unsure</l>
<l ln="16      ">Your breasts and understanding immature,</l>
<l ln="17      ">It was unnecessary to reveal soul</l>
<l ln="18      ">To one who merely asked you for the dole.</l>
<l ln="19      ">But then the blemish could be blamed on me</l>
<l ln="20      ">Who could discover sorrow in a tree</l>
<pb n="47">
<l ln="21      ">Or feel a joy that caused the blood to thrill</l>
<l ln="22      ">At baroque vases and a daffodil.</l>
<l ln="23      ">Happy the man oh happier by far</l>
<l ln="24      ">Who understands the belly of his car</l>
<l ln="25      ">And over half a pint becomes ecstatic</l>
<l ln="26      ">About acceleration in the traffic</l>
<l ln="27      ">The ruthless hand of God will never touch his head</l>
<l ln="28      ">Enter his toilet or defile his bed.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546869</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Leeds No.2</mainhead> <attbytes>6Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546869</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Leeds No.2</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000057</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000057</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Leeds No.2</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>6Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">The trams would grind up Beeston Hill</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Until well past midnight,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Squealing to a halt at Tempest Road</l>
<l ln="4        ">Then moaning along the cemetery</l>
<l ln="5        ">Into Beeston. Passing the pub</l>
<l ln="6        ">Where the barmaid&mdash;early Women's Lib&mdash;</l>
<l ln="7        ">Had given up wearing a bra.</l>
<l ln="8        ">At sixteen years of age I would drop pennies</l>
<l ln="9        ">Over the counter top to see her tits</l>
<l ln="10      ">When she obligingly bent down.</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;Dad's canaries would start to sing</l>
<l ln="12      ">Around five o'clock, so the nights were short.</l>
<l ln="13      ">By pulling the scrotum over the penis</l>
<l ln="14      ">You could almost persuade yourself</l>
<l ln="15      ">The itch between the crutch was imagination;</l>
<l ln="16      ">Though the stains on the sheets were biological enough</l>
<l ln="17      ">And were of course never talked about.</l>
<l ln="18      ">&indent;Sometimes we had a fitness fad</l>
<l ln="19      ">Walking through the grime to our window</l>
<l ln="20      ">Dressing jobs, believing we were breathing in fresh air.</l>
<l ln="21      ">At least we were chained at work</l>
<l ln="22      ">And did not have the time to think of life.</l>
<l ln="23      ">Did we realize we were alive?</l>
<l ln="24      ">The shop smelt of stale sweat and powder,</l>
<l ln="25      ">Armpit solicitations from a thousand women.</l>
<l ln="26      ">We used to laugh a lot because</l>
<pb n="48">
<l ln="27      ">We were too dulled to recognize sorrow.</l>
<l ln="28      ">Apart from death and a few cripples</l>
<l ln="29      ">Scrounging coppers outside Boar Lane Church</l>
<l ln="30      ">Nothing moved us as much as a good film.</l>
<l ln="31      ">Cooper, Cagney, Jean Arthur and Edward G.</l>
<l ln="32      ">Provided our view of reality.</l>
<l ln="33      ">&indent;At ten p.m. on Saturday</l>
<l ln="34      ">We slipped our leads and ran for home</l>
<l ln="35      ">Tired, dirty and dismayed about we knew not what.</l>
<l ln="36      ">Sunday, twice at chapel, sat upstairs</l>
<l ln="37      ">With Wally, eating peanuts. Reading</l>
<l ln="38      ">The Thriller, or making the choir girls laugh.</l>
<l ln="39      ">Once I smoked a fag during the prayer.</l>
<l ln="40      ">The congregation, retaining their seats and bowing</l>
<l ln="41      ">Their heads, looked as though they were</l>
<l ln="42      ">Engaged in a communal shit.</l>
<l ln="43      ">I could not honestly say that I was saved.</l>
<l ln="44      ">&indent;As for culture, a copy of</l>
<l ln="45      "><hi r="italic">The Good Companions</hi> lay about the house.</l>
<l ln="46      ">I knew one poem,</l>
<l ln="47      ">&ldquo;A garden is a lovesome thing&rdquo;, God, what</l>
<l ln="48      ">A load of rubbish. Strange,</l>
<l ln="49      ">I was not aware men still wrote poetry,</l>
<l ln="50      ">We would have thought it was unmanly.</l>
<l ln="51      ">My heart had not been hit, hurt or harassed</l>
<l ln="52      ">By any art. I liked Billy Bennett</l>
<l ln="53      ">At the Empire, now both levelled to the ground.</l>
<l ln="54      ">Somehow, I do not remember how</l>
<l ln="55      ">Or where, at the age of ten</l>
<l ln="56      ">I became a jazz fan and would cry</l>
<l ln="57      ">At Armstrong's West End Blues, and think</l>
<l ln="58      ">This weakness a barrier from my friends.</l>
<l ln="59      ">On four and nine a week I managed</l>
<l ln="60      ">To start collecting records and confirmed</l>
<l ln="61      ">My father's notion that he had whelped a fool,</l>
<l ln="62      ">Which I now realize was true,</l>
<l ln="63      ">Though at the time I did not think</l>
<l ln="64      ">In relative terms, but black and white.</l>
<l ln="65      ">My vanity made me unsure whether</l>
<l ln="66      ">I was on show in the windows</l>
<pb n="49">
<l ln="67      ">Or the clothes and dummies.</l>
<l ln="68      ">&indent;Standing watching Burton's and the Fifty Bob Tailor's</l>
<l ln="69      ">Cutters&mdash;shabby and consumptive looking&mdash;</l>
<l ln="70      ">Parading the streets for a shilling a week rise</l>
<l ln="71      ">Jolted my youthful conservatism.</l>
<l ln="72      ">And the first feel of a woman's cunt</l>
<l ln="73      ">Found my pinstriped trousers unprepared.</l>
<l ln="74      ">Was I growing up and making roots?</l>
<l ln="75      ">&indent;Cricket in Cross Flatts Park until lamplight.</l>
<l ln="76      ">I could run up to the wicket all grace</l>
<l ln="77      ">And lithesome youth, fast and accurate.</l>
<l ln="78      ">At silly point the swallows kept</l>
<l ln="79      ">A careful distance from my hands.</l>
<l ln="80      ">The West Riding recognized beauty</l>
<l ln="81      ">Applauding Hutton's off drive.</l>
<l ln="82      ">&indent;I have returned, but neither Leeds</l>
<l ln="83      ">Nor I have much to say to one another.</l>
<l ln="84      ">The city is cleaned up now. Poets get</l>
<l ln="85      ">Gregory Fellowships for no apparent reason</l>
<l ln="86      ">Apart from the right contacts in high places,</l>
<l ln="87      ">And I have failed to make money,</l>
<l ln="88      ">The only thing Leeds ever tried to teach me.</l>
<l ln="89      ">But I have succeeded in being a failure</l>
<l ln="90      ">And admit the fact&mdash;immodestly perhaps.</l>
<l ln="91      ">Sweet Street, where are you now!</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546870</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>St George's Wolverhampton</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546870</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>St George's Wolverhampton</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000058</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000058</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>St George's Wolverhampton</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">The shabbiness of the scene</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Is not offensive. The social tyrant</l>
<l ln="3        ">Might be affronted by the untidiness,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Being an ordered and disciplined soul,</l>
<l ln="5        ">But as our lives are shabby</l>
<l ln="6        ">And the details of daily living</l>
<l ln="7        ">Untidy, revealing a state of moral anarchy</l>
<l ln="8        ">That the car, Hoover, and cardboard house</l>
<pb n="50">
<l ln="9        ">Prove a poor substitute for,</l>
<l ln="10      ">One could say one was at home.</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;Somewhere to live is no problem</l>
<l ln="12      ">To find in the welfare state.</l>
<l ln="13      ">Clinical institutions, sterile and scrubbed,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Reduce the image of God to a filing cabinet,</l>
<l ln="15      ">Love is recognized by its absence.</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;Here, refusing to be confined within an ashtray,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Escaping the hawklike duster, it spreads</l>
<l ln="18      ">In untidy profusion throughout the house.</l>
<l ln="19      ">The physical symptoms experienced</l>
<l ln="20      ">Between two differently shaped bodies</l>
<l ln="21      ">Give a momentary illusion of</l>
<l ln="22      ">Unity, concealing the selfishness</l>
<l ln="23      ">Inherent in even satisfied desire.</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;But the imaginative love that one receives,</l>
<l ln="25      ">Which is never earned and seldom felt deserved,</l>
<l ln="26      ">Appears mysteriously from the empty air.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546871</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>For Mother</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546871</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>For Mother</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000059</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000059</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>For Mother</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">It was a good day for winter,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Though raining, it was mild</l>
<l ln="3        ">And the soil seemed pleased to receive</l>
<l ln="4        ">The remains of Hilda Harriet Louisa King,</l>
<l ln="5        ">My mother and first lover.</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;She died and was boxed on Boxing Day,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Thinking it unseemly, and being too humble</l>
<l ln="8        ">To intrude her death into the Child Christ's Day.</l>
<l ln="9        ">She had lived her latter years</l>
<l ln="10      ">Bewildered by pills and doctors' potions</l>
<l ln="11      ">For kidney, liver and a doubtful heart,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Attending to these matters as best as memory would allow.</l>
<l ln="13      ">&indent;But death, that great impersonator, slyly</l>
<l ln="14      ">Caught her with cerebral thrombosis,</l>
<l ln="15      ">One of the few complaints her</l>
<l ln="16      ">Imagination had not got around to.</l>
<pb n="51">
<l ln="17      ">&indent;She did nothing of any importance</l>
<l ln="18      ">And will not be mentioned in the history books.</l>
<l ln="19      ">Reared two indifferent children yet loved them,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Was loyal to one man through force of habit.</l>
<l ln="21      ">Her heart was never weak, her stomach strong,</l>
<l ln="22      ">At loving, few in the Riding could compare.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="23      ">&indent;If we shed tears, forgive us, she has found</l>
<l ln="24      ">Some peace on Stonefalls bleak and stony ground.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546872</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Distractions</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546872</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Distractions</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000060</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000060</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Distractions</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;Your postcards drop to earth</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Silent as paper darts thrown in the wind.</l>
<l ln="3        ">They come from where you are, but</l>
<l ln="4        ">Show one views of places you have been,</l>
<l ln="5        ">As if you wished to prove</l>
<l ln="6        ">That life was constant change,</l>
<l ln="7        ">And a relationship could not stand still.</l>
<l ln="8        ">Which I admit is true, although the dead</l>
<l ln="9        ">Are buried now in horizontal posture</l>
<l ln="10      ">Or burnt up at blast off.</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;What is written is not what</l>
<l ln="12      ">You wish to say, but a substitute</l>
<l ln="13      ">For words you dare not use.</l>
<l ln="14      ">&ldquo;Hope you are beginning to pick up,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="15      ">Means, &ldquo;because you left me you must</l>
<l ln="16      ">Be ill, get well soon, darling.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="17      ">&ldquo;You really must read Scott</l>
<l ln="18      ">Fitzgerald, you'll recognize</l>
<l ln="19      ">Some of the situations.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="20      ">This equates my few pints</l>
<l ln="21      ">And your nervous disorders,</l>
<l ln="22      ">With madness of a classic proportion</l>
<l ln="23      ">We neither could presume.</l>
<l ln="24      ">And though I make no answer to your missiles,</l>
<pb n="52">
<l ln="25      ">For two nights running I have prayed</l>
<l ln="26      ">&ldquo;Please, God, take this folly from me.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="27      ">&indent;Only to wake each morning, a murderer</l>
<l ln="28      ">With appetite unimpeded, tramping the lanes</l>
<l ln="29      ">Crying and talking to myself</l>
<l ln="30      ">Of injustice and hate.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546873</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Cows</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546873</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Cows</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000061</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000061</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Cows</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">At five o'clock the air is fresh</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And pimples one's shirt&hyphen;covered flesh,</l>
<l ln="3        ">The grass and kale stand firm and true</l>
<l ln="4        ">As soldiers, refreshed by the dew.</l>
<l ln="5        ">The beet is rigid for the hoe</l>
<l ln="6        ">And one can make a better show</l>
<l ln="7        ">At piece work when it holds its pride</l>
<l ln="8        ">Than later when the sun has dried</l>
<l ln="9        ">The moisture from its four&hyphen;leaved face</l>
<l ln="10      ">And it hangs limp about the place.</l>
<l ln="11      ">This is the fault of Charlie Brick</l>
<l ln="12      ">Who sowed the bloody seed too thick</l>
<l ln="13      ">And will be blamed with vulgar sounds</l>
<l ln="14      ">For robbing day&hyphen;men of the pounds</l>
<l ln="15      ">Intended to buy fattening pigs,</l>
<l ln="16      ">I hear the &ldquo;buggers&rdquo; and the &ldquo;frigs&rdquo;!</l>
<l ln="17      ">But Charlie's cunning and he will</l>
<l ln="18      ">Tell all the fault lies with the drill.</l>
<l ln="19      ">But I care &ldquo;nowt&rdquo; for drills and ploughs</l>
<l ln="20      ">Having a family of cows</l>
<l ln="21      ">That must be got into the shed</l>
<l ln="22      ">And groomed and washed and milked and fed.</l>
<l ln="23      ">I walk across the cuckoo Pen,</l>
<l ln="24      ">Notice the wires down again.</l>
<l ln="25      ">That's Marigold who scorns the jags</l>
<l ln="26      ">Where other cows respect their bags,</l>
<l ln="27      ">She jumps for clover, gets the shits</l>
<l ln="28      ">Mastitis and two damaged tits.</l>
<pb n="53">
<l ln="29      ">I shout &ldquo;come on&rdquo; and &ldquo;cupcupcup&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="30      ">And half the herd gets slowly up</l>
<l ln="31      ">Wandering as blindly to the shed</l>
<l ln="32      ">As man just risen from his bed.</l>
<l ln="33      ">Slowly, heads down, bent nearly double</l>
<l ln="34      ">As full of milk as man with trouble,</l>
<l ln="35      ">Except Suzanne who'll not concur</l>
<l ln="36      ">Until you put your boot in her.</l>
<l ln="37      ">She rises, stands, then coughs and shoots</l>
<l ln="38      ">A stream of shit on to your boots!</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546874</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>For Ann</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546874</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>For Ann</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000062</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000062</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>For Ann</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&indent;A woman of quality</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Is not created</l>
<l ln="3        ">Whole or wholesome,</l>
<l ln="4        ">And passes through the madness</l>
<l ln="5        ">God prescribes for those</l>
<l ln="6        ">Intent upon eternal knowledge.</l>
<l ln="7        ">&indent;A woman of quality</l>
<l ln="8        ">Learns to lie and cheat,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Becomes an artist in chicanery,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Holding her love like cards</l>
<l ln="11      ">Against her breast</l>
<l ln="12      ">Wanting to trump</l>
<l ln="13      ">Everybody's aces,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Yet never believes she can be loved</l>
<l ln="15      ">And makes demands</l>
<l ln="16      ">Beyond man's frail ability.</l>
<l ln="17      ">&indent;A woman of quality</l>
<l ln="18      ">Learns through guilt</l>
<l ln="19      ">The secrets of the heart,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Wearing her two black eyes</l>
<l ln="21      ">Like bright and shining stars.</l>
<l ln="22      ">&indent;A woman of quality can say</l>
<l ln="23      ">&ldquo;It was as much my fault as yours,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="24      ">And kiss the drunken fist so full of folly.</l>
<pb n="54">
<l ln="25      ">&indent;A woman of quality</l>
<l ln="26      ">Asks for nothing, forgives all</l>
<l ln="27      ">And is imperfect, but aware</l>
<l ln="28      ">In the shattering hours of night</l>
<l ln="29      ">Of the holiness of life.</l>
<l ln="30      ">&indent;The imperfections of man are revealed</l>
<l ln="31      ">When I can no longer love you,</l>
<l ln="32      ">And have forgotten the ecstasy we suffered</l>
<l ln="33      ">Because your neck grows scraggy.</l>
<l ln="34      ">Yet seeing you lost and lonely</l>
<l ln="35      ">In the gaiety of the crowded hall</l>
<l ln="36      ">I am overcome by memories and grief.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546875</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>For Charles Sisson</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546875</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>For Charles Sisson</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000063</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000063</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>For Charles Sisson</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Old friend, the spirit</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Places us with sundry moves,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Into areas we</l>
<l ln="4        ">Have no wish to be.</l>
<l ln="5        ">And the pattern is laid down,</l>
<l ln="6        ">You stay in the town</l>
<l ln="7        ">Fingering at weekends</l>
<l ln="8        ">The fabric of the countryside:</l>
<l ln="9        ">While I try to compress</l>
<l ln="10      ">The whole of nature into my body</l>
<l ln="11      ">Yet seldom use the eyes</l>
<l ln="12      ">In proper country style</l>
<l ln="13      ">And ache for a town that I despise.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="14      ">You have little to say to me</l>
<l ln="15      ">And my ears recognize</l>
<l ln="16      ">My mouth's trivialities,</l>
<l ln="17      ">While my pen is incontinent.</l>
<l ln="18      ">Should we meet&mdash;</l>
<l ln="19      ">Over the plastic menu</l>
<l ln="20      ">The ritual libation in Guinness</l>
<l ln="21      ">To the fickle muse&mdash;</l>
<pb n="55">
<l ln="22      ">We sit out the long silences</l>
<l ln="23      ">Watching the vulgarity of the masses</l>
<l ln="24      ">In Leicester Square,</l>
<l ln="25      ">Or searching the dustbins</l>
<l ln="26      ">Of our minds for something</l>
<l ln="27      ">We hold in common&mdash;</l>
<l ln="28      ">Other than our fallen state.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="29      ">We have our individual</l>
<l ln="30      ">Brand of happiness and</l>
<l ln="31      ">This does not demand</l>
<l ln="32      ">That our faces express it.</l>
<l ln="33      ">So as you heave your left leg</l>
<l ln="34      ">Forward in characteristic gait,</l>
<l ln="35      ">Your face does not find it necessary</l>
<l ln="36      ">To show excessive pleasure</l>
<l ln="37      ">Or even a mild irritation</l>
<l ln="38      ">As we reconstruct our last</l>
<l ln="39      ">And every conversation.</l>
<l ln="40      ">We do not walk with God,</l>
<l ln="41      ">Though we both know</l>
<l ln="42      ">We cannot walk without Him.</l>
<l ln="43      ">Death is a desirable state</l>
<l ln="44      ">Preferably swift, or should one hope</l>
<l ln="45      ">Mercifully? Not only</l>
<l ln="46      ">Because men are ugly</l>
<l ln="47      ">But the world is too beautiful to bear</l>
<l ln="48      ">And we are constrained</l>
<l ln="49      ">To love the whole</l>
<l ln="50      ">And each and every unpleasant member.</l>
<l ln="51      ">An impossible task</l>
<l ln="52      ">For a warped mind</l>
<l ln="53      ">Combined with an impure heart.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="54      ">When every day was fine</l>
<l ln="55      ">And innocent treble sang</l>
<l ln="56      ">&ldquo;You in your small corner</l>
<l ln="57      ">And I in mine,&rdquo;</l>
<pb n="56">
<l ln="58      ">Was the vast distance</l>
<l ln="59      ">Between the corners appreciated,</l>
<l ln="60      ">Or how tiny the space</l>
<l ln="61      ">Required to contain us.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546876</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>After Attending a Poetry Jazz Session</mainhead> <attbytes>5Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546876</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>After Attending a Poetry Jazz Session</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000064</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000064</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>After Attending a Poetry Jazz Session</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>5Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Having been affianced to jazz</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Since the age of eight and listened</l>
<l ln="3        ">With a child's grave wonder to Armstrong's West End Blues;</l>
<l ln="4        ">Wept adolescent tears at Ellington,</l>
<l ln="5        ">I viewed with trepidation the meeting</l>
<l ln="6        ">Of an earlier and constant lover</l>
<l ln="7        ">With a later flame, the bitch poetry.</l>
<l ln="8        ">The cultural aura of Crouch End</l>
<l ln="9        ">Is conjured only with the help of alcohol</l>
<l ln="10      ">And the border between sensibility</l>
<l ln="11      ">Where mind, body and spirit are fused in one,</l>
<l ln="12      ">And insensibility, is easily over&hyphen;run</l>
<l ln="13      ">But on this occasion, passport out of date,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Pocket having no chink for a drink,</l>
<l ln="15      ">The ordeal demanded more courage</l>
<l ln="16      ">Than I can customarily muster.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="17      ">Whether the jazz being played on entry</l>
<l ln="18      ">Was &ldquo;avant garde&rdquo; or &ldquo;mainstream&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="19      ">I am unable to say, but Slam Stewart</l>
<l ln="20      ">Played the bass solo thirty years ago.</l>
<l ln="21      ">Ah! the young are unaware that history</l>
<l ln="22      ">Like sin repeats itself &ldquo;ad nauseam&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="23      ">Accepting as &ldquo;meaningful&rdquo; and &ldquo;vital&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="24      ">The washed out words of weary poets</l>
<l ln="25      ">And the crude chords of a barbaric piano.</l>
<pb n="57">
<l ln="26      ">When the cutting contest began, the musicians</l>
<l ln="27      ">Carved the poets into tiny pieces,</l>
<l ln="28      ">Being professional, masters of their instruments,</l>
<l ln="29      ">Making profounder and more forthright statements</l>
<l ln="30      ">In a clear tone for all to hear.</l>
<l ln="31      ">They reduced the poets to mutterers,</l>
<l ln="32      ">Sighing shaming sins at the confessional.</l>
<l ln="33      ">The unhappy affair on the Serpentine&mdash;</l>
<l ln="34      ">That ended in a wet shirt front.</l>
<l ln="35      ">The eccentricity of being out of tune</l>
<l ln="36      ">With the disastrous times one was born in,</l>
<l ln="37      ">Unacceptable in Soho,</l>
<l ln="38      ">Considered gaga in Golders Green.</l>
<l ln="39      ">Where has the son of woman to lay his head?</l>
<l ln="40      ">The undergraduate Milton, blind</l>
<l ln="41      ">But articulate at the bar, where the locals</l>
<l ln="42      ">Listened in amazement to his</l>
<l ln="43      ">Erudite discussion on Arnold.</l>
<l ln="44      ">Or the poetic preacher, guilty</l>
<l ln="45      ">Of three marriages and prouder of this&hyphen;than</l>
<l ln="46      ">Any poem signed by his bankrupt pen.</l>
<l ln="47      ">The final poet, anonymous as a paving stone,</l>
<l ln="48      ">Made remarks, stuttered statements,</l>
<l ln="49      ">As I made my way to the exit.</l>
<l ln="50      ">Not one line remains to please,</l>
<l ln="51      ">Appease or comfort the heavy heart.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="52      ">I hurry home to my &ldquo;poems two a penny&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="53      ">Born out of seventeen years shit&hyphen;shovelling,</l>
<l ln="54      ">Sired by vanity, a stallion who</l>
<l ln="55      ">Rushes me up most unlikely roads</l>
<l ln="56      ">Hard of mouth, uncontrollable,</l>
<l ln="57      ">Takes the bit between his yellow teeth,</l>
<l ln="58      ">Ignores my feeble pull upon the reins,</l>
<l ln="59      ">Reducing me to an incoherence</l>
<l ln="60      ">Understood by two or three maniacs</l>
<l ln="61      ">Who with loving generosity</l>
<l ln="62      ">See fit to call me friend.</l>
<l ln="63      ">There is beauty in every seen thing,</l>
<pb n="58">
<l ln="64      ">Rain and cloud, the sun, impersonal star.</l>
<l ln="65      ">Sometimes when absorption with myself</l>
<l ln="66      ">Is broken by a sudden shaft of insight,</l>
<l ln="67      ">For a moment I marvel at grass,</l>
<l ln="68      ">The sound of sparrows, amazed</l>
<l ln="69      ">At a world, grey as this wet Monday.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546877</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Impromptu Poetry</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546877</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Impromptu Poetry</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
