<newatts><attidref>X2000065</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Impromptu Poetry</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<div3><comhd3 r="italic"><idref>Z300546878</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<hi r="roman">I</hi> Shouting for Joy <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546878</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Impromptu Poetry</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">I Shouting for Joy</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Lord when I put on a dean shirt</l>
<l ln="3        ">Would you do me dirt?</l>
<l ln="4        ">When I cry</l>
<l ln="5        ">To a grey sky,</l>
<l ln="6        ">&ldquo;Thank you,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="7        ">For having nothing to do,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Would you, loving God</l>
<l ln="9        ">Thwack me with your heavenly rod?</l>
<l ln="10      ">If I learn to lie and cheat,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Scrounge money and the food I eat,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Behave in a million styles,</l>
<l ln="13      ">With alcohol distract my piles,</l>
<l ln="14      ">What the hell can you do,</l>
<l ln="15      ">I still belong to you.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="16      ">If I join the Civil Service Thou art there,</l>
<l ln="17      ">In my bed, pint pot, bogs, everywhere.</l>
<l ln="18      ">When I touch the virginal tit,</l>
<l ln="19      ">Read the writing on the wall when I shit</l>
<l ln="20      ">All that I view is a reflection of You.</l>
<l ln="21      ">Wonderful are Thy ways,</l>
<l ln="22      ">Unhappy are my days:</l>
<l ln="23      ">In all I see</l>
<l ln="24      ">The world is too lovely.</l></pdiv></div3>
<pb n="59">
<div3><comhd3 r="italic"><idref>Z300546879</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<hi r="roman">II</hi> Prayer <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546879</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Impromptu Poetry</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<l ln="25      ">As I laid in bed this morning</l>
<l ln="26      ">My hand upon my tool,</l>
<l ln="27      ">I cried &ldquo;O Lord forgive me</l>
<l ln="28      ">I have been a bloody fool,</l>
<l ln="29      ">Thinking that conversation</l>
<l ln="30      ">With Your August self must start</l>
<l ln="31      ">In some sepulchral chapel</l>
<l ln="32      ">With my hand upon my heart&rdquo;.</l></div3>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546880</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Downs and Ups</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546880</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Downs and Ups</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000066</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000066</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Downs and Ups</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">When I contract my belly in</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Defy the mirror with a grin</l>
<l ln="3        ">Yet mark the slackness of the skin</l>
<l ln="4        ">The impact hits me on the chin.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="5        ">Or drifting in the train to town</l>
<l ln="6        ">Past Ferme Park Up and Ferme Park Down</l>
<l ln="7        ">Although perhaps I act the clown</l>
<l ln="8        ">There's always holly in the crown.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">At morning when the dogs of dark</l>
<l ln="10      ">Sit silent, never raise a bark,</l>
<l ln="11      ">I wander Alexandra Park</l>
<l ln="12      ">Praising the Lord, blessed by the lark.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546881</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Wingfield Priory</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546881</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Wingfield Priory</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000067</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000067</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Wingfield Priory</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">My heart there is a home</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Where the mind is easier.</l>
<l ln="3        ">The evening sky, red,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Setting behind hedge and</l>
<pb n="60">
<l ln="5        ">Paddock gate in the glory</l>
<l ln="6        ">Of the everlasting Light.</l>
<l ln="7        ">Barn with axe cut beams,</l>
<l ln="8        ">The whole demanding</l>
<l ln="9        ">Respect by its very age,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Early Tudor&mdash;and my late love.</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;It had stood the years so quietly,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Even the birds accepted it</l>
<l ln="13      ">As a friend, and all who</l>
<l ln="14      ">Lived within its plastered walls.</l>
<l ln="15      ">&indent;Winter, when first it</l>
<l ln="16      ">Met my jaded eyes,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Saw ducks sliding on ponds</l>
<l ln="18      ">One of which was</l>
<l ln="19      ">Watering a golden pheasant,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Who flew away, shocked</l>
<l ln="21      ">At man's ill&hyphen;mannered entrance.</l>
<l ln="22      ">We wandered up and down</l>
<l ln="23      ">In, out and all around.</l>
<l ln="24      ">Evening stole upon us</l>
<l ln="25      ">And found us loath to leave,</l>
<l ln="26      ">Until the frost drove</l>
<l ln="27      ">Us back to London, silent</l>
<l ln="28      ">As sinners before the mercy seat.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="29      ">&indent;Cap in hand through</l>
<l ln="30      ">Family, foe and friend</l>
<l ln="31      ">I asked for money</l>
<l ln="32      ">And was not refused,</l>
<l ln="33      ">Until it seemed that God</l>
<l ln="34      ">Had found some purpose</l>
<l ln="35      ">For my useless hands,</l>
<l ln="36      ">Or so my vanity assumed.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="37      ">&indent;Come June I stood</l>
<l ln="38      ">Among the uncut grass,</l>
<l ln="39      ">Guinea fowl cry</l>
<l ln="40      ">&ldquo;Come quick, come quick,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="41      ">Or, &ldquo;Grey grey grey,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="42      ">Echoing all around.</l>
<pb n="61">
<l ln="43      ">From underneath the eaves</l>
<l ln="44      ">Swallows, swifts and martins</l>
<l ln="45      ">Swooped, flicking across my eyes.</l>
<l ln="46      ">The sky&mdash;East Anglian blue,</l>
<l ln="47      ">Shrubs, scents, bees, briars</l>
<l ln="48      ">Were shriven by refining sun.</l>
<l ln="49      ">And should I not weep for joy?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="50      ">&indent;Surrounded by loved ones,</l>
<l ln="51      ">My study lined with books</l>
<l ln="52      ">Written by my betters,</l>
<l ln="53      ">I sat, fat with feeling</l>
<l ln="54      ">Waiting for words to set me free.</l>
<l ln="55      ">&indent;But from every window</l>
<l ln="56      ">Life set out to distract me.</l>
<l ln="57      ">A blackcap sat upon my table</l>
<l ln="58      ">Questioning my words and motives.</l>
<l ln="59      ">A bullfinch pecked a poppy seed.</l>
<l ln="60      ">A tit, feet fixed in fat,</l>
<l ln="61      ">Swung in a sudden gale</l>
<l ln="62      ">The clock round in a second.</l>
<l ln="63      ">Six cock pheasants called for supper.</l>
<l ln="64      ">A pair of pigeons nested in the barn.</l>
<l ln="65      ">&indent;The days drew to their close</l>
<l ln="66      ">And my paper bore no marks.</l>
<l ln="67      ">&indent;Standing in the ingle&hyphen;nook,</l>
<l ln="68      ">Looking up the pit black stack</l>
<l ln="69      ">Towards the tiny disc of heaven,</l>
<l ln="70      ">I recognized my failure;</l>
<l ln="71      ">Only time revealed my small success.</l>
<l ln="72      ">But that was after I had run</l>
<l ln="73      ">To a town where the living are stunted,</l>
<l ln="74      ">And one can feel almost one's proper height.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="62">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546882</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Pets</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546882</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Pets</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000068</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000068</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Pets</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">I am surrounded by pets.</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Three caged birds, a cat&mdash;</l>
<l ln="3        ">Emasculated, of course&mdash;</l>
<l ln="4        ">Two poodles and a dalmatian.</l>
<l ln="5        ">They, the dogs and the cats</l>
<l ln="6        ">Eat food from tins</l>
<l ln="7        ">Filled by an industry</l>
<l ln="8        ">That recognizes a sucker</l>
<l ln="9        ">When it sees one.</l>
<l ln="10      ">The birds, exotic creatures,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Cannot sing; anyway,</l>
<l ln="12      ">What have they got to sing about?</l>
<l ln="13      ">But they utter a few words&mdash;</l>
<l ln="14      ">That justifies their captivity.</l>
<l ln="15      ">The mynah bird repeats</l>
<l ln="16      ">&ldquo;Silly bugger&rdquo;, a proper</l>
<l ln="17      ">Judgement on its owners.</l>
<l ln="18      ">They exist to channel off the love</l>
<l ln="19      ">That cannot be given to</l>
<l ln="20      ">The brotherhood of foolish men.</l>
<l ln="21      ">And of course they never</l>
<l ln="22      ">Disagree or answer back.</l>
<l ln="23      ">I wish someone would</l>
<l ln="24      ">Have me for a pet.</l>
<l ln="25      ">I would sit upon my perch</l>
<l ln="26      ">And the silly things I say</l>
<l ln="27      ">That now annoy, would give such pleasure.</l>
<l ln="28      ">And nobody would expect</l>
<l ln="29      ">Me to say &ldquo;thank you&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="30      ">When I pecked your finger</l>
<l ln="31      ">You would think it fun</l>
<l ln="32      ">And not reprove me.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="33      ">Please, God,</l>
<l ln="34      ">If I can't be a man,</l>
<l ln="35      ">May I be a pet?</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="63">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546883</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Nothing Doing</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546883</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Nothing Doing</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000069</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000069</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Nothing Doing</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Nothing drives me back</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Neither the sleepless nights</l>
<l ln="3        ">Nor the sprays of May</l>
<l ln="4        ">The things I lack</l>
<l ln="5        ">Or the imagined delights</l>
<l ln="6        ">Of lovers at play.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="7        ">Along country lanes</l>
<l ln="8        ">Where memories are erased,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Above the petrol fumes, suddenly,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Such scents pierce my nose</l>
<l ln="11      ">That I stand still, amazed</l>
<l ln="12      ">I should have missed</l>
<l ln="13      ">The faintest odour from the earth</l>
<l ln="14      ">Fragrance of the dog rose.</l>
<l ln="15      ">&indent;Dalmatian, dog nose</l>
<l ln="16      ">Grounded over wayside soil,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Stops at my sudden beginning.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546884</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Deficiencies</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546884</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Deficiencies</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000070</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000070</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Deficiencies</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Yours is the culinary triumph</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Mine the obese disgrace</l>
<l ln="3        ">I grow so thin in spirit</l>
<l ln="4        ">As I grow fat in face.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="64">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546885</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>For Patrick John Walton
<subhead>born 4 November 1971</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546885</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>For Patrick John Walton  born 4 November 1971</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000071</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000071</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>For Patrick John Walton  born 4 November 1971</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Patrick John Walton, my first grandchild.</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Named after two fishermen,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Fourteen days old and unversed still</l>
<l ln="4        ">In the art of casting for compliments.</l>
<l ln="5        ">&indent;We have not met yet. We have the time</l>
<l ln="6        ">But neither of us has the money.</l>
<l ln="7        ">So all I know about you is</l>
<l ln="8        ">The colour of your hair, brown and thick,</l>
<l ln="9        ">And your shoulders are described as</l>
<l ln="10      ">&ldquo;Like a bull's,&rdquo; which means</l>
<l ln="11      ">Your Grandmama has placed</l>
<l ln="12      ">Her masterprint upon your flesh.</l>
<l ln="13      ">&indent;I was pleased that you were</l>
<l ln="14      ">Disinclined to rush into the world,</l>
<l ln="15      ">Selfishly I must admit</l>
<l ln="16      ">As your mother was growing tired</l>
<l ln="17      ">Of carrying your burden in her belly.</l>
<l ln="18      ">But now we hold in common, besides our sex,</l>
<l ln="19      ">We both are Scorpios,</l>
<l ln="20      ">And I am curious to see</l>
<l ln="21      ">If you handle the problems of living</l>
<l ln="22      ">With greater aplomb and skill than me</l>
<l ln="23      ">Who find life's sting grows fiercer at the tail.</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;I feel that I should give you some advice</l>
<l ln="25      ">To help you on your journey to the tomb</l>
<l ln="26      ">But what have I to say? The moon</l>
<l ln="27      ">Is not green cheese, living is rough</l>
<l ln="28      ">And that I think is really far enough.</l>
<l ln="29      ">Besides, I don't think you would wish to know,</l>
<l ln="30      ">I know I never did, I had to learn</l>
<l ln="31      ">Or anyway to live the drama of the days,</l>
<l ln="32      ">Or is it melodrama knocks me out?</l>
<l ln="33      ">&indent;A couple of things I'll mention then I'll dose.</l>
<l ln="34      ">Don't mix the grape with grain</l>
<l ln="35      ">The pain is not relieved</l>
<l ln="36      ">By drinking gripewater.</l>
<l ln="37      ">And never let the muse bemuse you</l>
<pb n="65">
<l ln="38      ">Into trying to write verse</l>
<l ln="39      ">It's hard work, and the punishment</l>
<l ln="40      ">Is greater than the crime.</l>
<l ln="41      ">&indent;Go out into the world as you are now</l>
<l ln="42      ">Naked and in love with everyone.</l>
<l ln="43      ">Lead with your chin.</l>
<l ln="44      ">To hold compassion from mankind</l>
<l ln="45      ">Is the one sin</l>
<l ln="46      ">You should avoid.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="47      ">Good luck, Pat, if I remember to</l>
<l ln="48      ">I'll send a card each year</l>
<l ln="49      ">And say a prayer for you.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546886</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Latter Day Psalms</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546886</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Latter Day Psalms</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000072</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000072</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Latter Day Psalms</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546887</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

1 <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546887</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Latter Day Psalms</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Somewhere there is Grace, Lord,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Was I not told it as a child</l>
<l ln="3        ">When the sound of the sparrow</l>
<l ln="4        ">Filled my heart with delight</l>
<l ln="5        ">And the rain fell like friendship on my head.</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;Now the call of the cuckoo</l>
<l ln="7        ">Cannot calm my aching heart,</l>
<l ln="8        ">And my soul is tormented with fear.</l>
<l ln="9        ">&indent;Have mercy, Lord, for I have travelled far</l>
<l ln="10      ">Yet all my knowledge is as nothing.</l>
<l ln="11      ">My days are numbered. Time titters</l>
<l ln="12      ">As I stumble down the street.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="13      ">Forgiveness, O forgive me, Lord,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Close my critical eye</l>
<l ln="15      ">Take me to your breast</l>
<l ln="16      ">For how else may I die.</l></pdiv></div3>
<pb n="66">
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546888</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

2 <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546888</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Latter Day Psalms</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<pdiv><l ln="17      ">The tree waves in the wind</l>
<l ln="18      ">But does not break unless</l>
<l ln="19      ">The bough is over&hyphen;burdened.</l>
<l ln="20      ">When spring disrupts the dead days</l>
<l ln="21      ">Buds, leaves, and birds praise God</l>
<l ln="22      ">In song and silent sound.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="23      ">&indent;The dead dock, stiff</l>
<l ln="24      ">With last year's pride,</l>
<l ln="25      ">Leans unwillingly in the gale.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="26      ">&indent;My heart, Lord, is unyielding,</l>
<l ln="27      ">My joints are stiff.</l>
<l ln="28      ">The knuckles of my knees</l>
<l ln="29      ">Refuse to bend.</l>
<l ln="30      ">The knife is at my neck,</l>
<l ln="31      ">My back breaks.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="32      ">&indent;I will say my matutinal prayers</l>
<l ln="33      ">From a crippled position,</l>
<l ln="34      ">Perhaps the Lord will hear?</l></pdiv></div3>
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546889</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

3 <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546889</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Latter Day Psalms</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<l ln="35      ">I lived among lewd men</l>
<l ln="36      ">Beneath the Crouch End clock,</l>
<l ln="37      ">Waiting for God to speak.</l>
<l ln="38      ">But my ears were dull</l>
<l ln="39      ">And what my brain received</l>
<l ln="40      ">My mind misunderstood.</l>
<l ln="41      ">So I took my mean heart to the hills,</l>
<l ln="42      ">Beside the Palace of Alexandra</l>
<l ln="43      ">Gazed on Barbican and grieved.</l>
<l ln="44      ">&indent;Lord speak to me in the morning</l>
<l ln="45      ">&indent;Or the night will be everlasting.</l>
<l ln="46      ">Now all the dogs of Dewsbury</l>
<l ln="47      ">Bay about my heels,</l>
<l ln="48      ">And the foul water of the Calder</l>
<l ln="49      ">Weeps into the sea.</l></div3>
<pb n="67">
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546890</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

4 <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546890</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Latter Day Psalms</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<l ln="50      ">On the estate, Lord, the people</l>
<l ln="51      ">Take counsel one with another,</l>
<l ln="52      ">And in the public house</l>
<l ln="53      ">There is lamentation.</l>
<l ln="54      ">The cost of living soars</l>
<l ln="55      ">Like wild duck rising</l>
<l ln="56      ">After morning feed.</l>
<l ln="57      ">Man has neither means nor meaning.</l>
<l ln="58      ">The cry of the young in the street</l>
<l ln="59      ">Rouses a protest in the market place.</l>
<l ln="60      ">&indent;What shall I do, Lord?</l>
<l ln="61      ">Though I bring my sad soul</l>
<l ln="62      ">And place it at Your feet,</l>
<l ln="63      ">My mouth is bitter, for fear</l>
<l ln="64      ">Infects my hand and heart.</l>
<l ln="65      ">The pit of hell yawns wide</l>
<l ln="66      ">Before my floundering feet,</l>
<l ln="67      ">I slip, I slide, I fall,</l>
<l ln="68      ">I try to grasp a skylark</l>
<l ln="69      ">But it flies south for summer.</l>
<l ln="70      ">&indent;My mind is melancholic,</l>
<l ln="71      ">&indent;I cannot praise my maker.</l></div3>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546891</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>A Stranger in This Land</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546891</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>A Stranger in This Land</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000073</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000073</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Stranger in This Land</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Lord, I am lonely</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And the sun is shining,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Listless, while the wind</l>
<l ln="4        ">Shakes the ageing leaves.</l>
<l ln="5        ">The harvest has been gathered</l>
<l ln="6        ">All is bagged and barned,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Silos burst with grain.</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;Why, Lord, must I still stand</l>
<l ln="9        ">Dropping blind seeds</l>
<l ln="10      ">On to a barren soil?</l>
<pb n="68">
<l ln="11      ">Come, sweet Jesus, cut me down</l>
<l ln="12      ">With the sickle of Your mercy,</l>
<l ln="13      ">For I am lonely</l>
<l ln="14      ">And a stranger in this land.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546892</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>An Adaptation of a Translation
<subhead>by C.H. Sisson</subhead></mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546892</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>An Adaptation of a Translation  by C.H. Sisson</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000074</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000074</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>An Adaptation of a Translation  by C.H. Sisson</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">What fer do 'e bash me</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">'Til oi do moan?</l>
<l ln="3        ">I an't said nought 'gen 'im</l>
<l ln="4        ">I an't dun ought 'gen 'im</l>
<l ln="5        ">Jus' talkin' to ole Jim</l>
<l ln="6        ">We was alone.</l>
<l ln="7        ">What fer do 'e bash me</l>
<l ln="8        ">'Til oi do moan?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">If 'e doan' let oi be</l>
<l ln="10      ">Oi'll pay 'im back 'e'll see</l>
<l ln="11      ">'E can't do this to me</l>
<l ln="12      ">Or oi'll be goin'</l>
<l ln="13      ">What fer do'e bash me</l>
<l ln="14      ">'Til oi do moan?</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="15      ">Knows what do raise 'is spunk</l>
<l ln="16      ">When 'e with ale be drunk</l>
<l ln="17      ">Oi'll creep into Jim's bunk</l>
<l ln="18      ">Stark as a stone.</l>
<l ln="19      ">What fer do 'e bash me</l>
<l ln="20      ">'Til oi do moan?</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="69">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546893</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>For Rachael</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546893</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>For Rachael</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000075</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000075</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>For Rachael</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">God give you both a gentle child</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Unfrightened by the winter's wild</l>
<l ln="3        ">Winds, the baying of the crowd,</l>
<l ln="4        ">The cruel tongues and loud</l>
<l ln="5        ">Lies of ignorant men. Let</l>
<l ln="6        ">Her seek a world where she can find</l>
<l ln="7        ">Food for an innocent mind</l>
<l ln="8        ">And heart. Where she can learn</l>
<l ln="9        ">That when the passions start to burn</l>
<l ln="10      ">The flesh, both lion and dove</l>
<l ln="11      ">Are the true elements of true love.</l>
<l ln="12      ">Pray God, she never may feel shame</l>
<l ln="13      ">For either parent, neither blame</l>
<l ln="14      ">Them for sins common to the world</l>
<l ln="15      ">Before their own flesh was uncurled.</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;Let her walk through life as through some cool glade</l>
<l ln="17      ">Where tired and hungry may seek and find shade.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546894</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Gone and Forgotten</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546894</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Gone and Forgotten</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000076</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000076</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Gone and Forgotten</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">A piece of land</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Where people lived</l>
<l ln="3        ">And died.</l>
<l ln="4        ">Children played</l>
<l ln="5        ">And worry ploughed</l>
<l ln="6        ">A furrow on the brow.</l>
<l ln="7        ">&indent;All gone.</l>
<l ln="8        ">No stone still stands</l>
<l ln="9        ">Or if it does</l>
<l ln="10      ">The remnants of a garden</l>
<l ln="11      ">Hide the ruins.</l>
<l ln="12      ">The cultivated rose</l>
<l ln="13      ">Is running wild</l>
<l ln="14      ">Acacias battle</l>
<l ln="15      ">Through the weeds.</l>
<pb n="70">
<l ln="16      ">&indent;From the straight</l>
<l ln="17      ">Backed ash</l>
<l ln="18      ">A robin sings</l>
<l ln="19      ">A moment, not</l>
<l ln="20      ">In love, but</l>
<l ln="21      ">Celebrating the</l>
<l ln="22      ">Remnants of an</l>
<l ln="23      ">Ill&hyphen;remembered summer.</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;Winter lurks</l>
<l ln="25      ">Just around the corner.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546895</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Walking with my Grandchild Rachael in Early Morning</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546895</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Walking with my Grandchild Rachael in Early Morning</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000077</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000077</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Walking with my Grandchild Rachael in Early Morning</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Silence underlines</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The punctuality</l>
<l ln="3        ">Of the tractor driver.</l>
<l ln="4        ">A cry from farm</l>
<l ln="5        ">Building and the</l>
<l ln="6        ">Patient cattle's hooves</l>
<l ln="7        ">Crackle over the</l>
<l ln="8        ">Stiff stubble.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="9        ">Morning mist creates</l>
<l ln="10      ">Phantoms and illusions</l>
<l ln="11      ">Flat becomes upright</l>
<l ln="12      ">Distance loses ground</l>
<l ln="13      ">Plovers and seagulls</l>
<l ln="14      ">Rise from earth</l>
<l ln="15      ">Bound clouds</l>
<l ln="16      ">The cock performs</l>
<l ln="17      ">His work of</l>
<l ln="18      ">Supererogation.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="19      ">&indent;&ldquo;Run, Grandad!&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="20      ">I become the</l>
<l ln="21      ">Entertainer once</l>
<l ln="22      ">Again.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="71">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546896</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Happy Families</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546896</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Happy Families</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000078</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000078</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Happy Families</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">You shall not have my dog.</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">I offered it</l>
<l ln="3        ">And you refused</l>
<l ln="4        ">Because you were afraid,</l>
<l ln="5        ">You shall not have my dog.</l>
<l ln="6        "><hi r="italic">He</hi> used to read my letters,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Sat in my chair</l>
<l ln="8        ">Touching things on my table</l>
<l ln="9        ">When my back was turned.</l>
<l ln="10      ">I never liked <hi r="italic">him</hi></l>
<l ln="11      ">For the man's a fool</l>
<l ln="12      ">And like all fools</l>
<l ln="13      ">Blown up with self conceit,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Were you so witless</l>
<l ln="15      ">That you had to wed <hi r="italic">him?</hi></l>
<l ln="16      ">You shall not have my dog.</l>
<l ln="17      ">Where are the shelves</l>
<l ln="18      "><hi r="italic">He</hi> promised to put up,</l>
<l ln="19      ">The rods inside the cupboard</l>
<l ln="20      ">To hang clothes on?</l>
<l ln="21      "><hi r="italic">He</hi> smells of smoke</l>
<l ln="22      ">And I'm ashamed</l>
<l ln="23      ">To own <hi r="italic">him</hi> as</l>
<l ln="24      ">A son&hyphen;in&hyphen;law.</l>
<l ln="25      ">You shall not have my dog</l>
<l ln="26      ">To spoil like my grandchildren,</l>
<l ln="27      ">Bed at all hours,</l>
<l ln="28      ">Fretting all day</l>
<l ln="29      ">For sweets and toys,</l>
<l ln="30      ">Touching my books.</l>
<l ln="31      ">Refusing decent fruit,</l>
<l ln="32      ">Asking for more with</l>
<l ln="33      ">Fist still full of food.</l>
<l ln="34      ">Stew in your own juice</l>
<l ln="35      ">And I'll stew in mine,</l>
<l ln="36      ">You shall not have my dog</l>
<l ln="37      ">Not even if you ask.</l>
<l ln="38      ">You shall not have my dog!</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="72">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546897</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>My Lady</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546897</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>My Lady</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000079</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000079</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>My Lady</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">My lady has gathered</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Up her purse, said goodbye</l>
<l ln="3        ">And caught the bus to Batley.</l>
<l ln="4        ">I sit in the Little Saddle</l>
<l ln="5        ">Morosely drinking gin,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Thinking of My Lady's</l>
<l ln="7        ">Eyes, sweetness of breath</l>
<l ln="8        ">Breasts like summer roses.</l>
<l ln="9        ">In Market Street, the cars</l>
<l ln="10      ">Snarl at pedestrians</l>
<l ln="11      ">Crossing the road with</l>
<l ln="12      ">Chronic indecision.</l>
<l ln="13      ">Sun drops down winter blue</l>
<l ln="14      ">Life is implacable.</l>
<l ln="15      ">My lady has gathered</l>
<l ln="16      ">Up her purse, said goodbye</l>
<l ln="17      ">And caught the bus to Batley,</l>
<l ln="18      ">A stranger dips his fingers</l>
<l ln="19      ">In her purse.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546898</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Langport Poem</mainhead> <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546898</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Langport Poem</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000080</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000080</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Langport Poem</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>4Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">I was born</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">But for what purpose</l>
<l ln="3        ">Time has not made plain</l>
<l ln="4        ">But time, nibbling</l>
<l ln="5        ">Mouselike at my years,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Has left me but little while</l>
<l ln="7        ">To put a meaning</l>
<l ln="8        ">To my father's frenzied moment.</l>
<l ln="9        ">&indent;Once, when I was young,</l>
<l ln="10      ">And life was lovely,</l>
<l ln="11      ">To love the ugly</l>
<l ln="12      ">Help the lame to walk</l>
<l ln="13      ">Was all I wished.</l>
<pb n="73">
<l ln="14      ">Pity was easy</l>
<l ln="15      ">Compassion came tardily.</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;The ideals of the young</l>
<l ln="17      ">One must admire,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Toying with broken bones</l>
<l ln="19      ">And bodies all askew,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Wearing a Christian face</l>
<l ln="21      ">Or a Buddhist attitude</l>
<l ln="22      ">The wickedness of man</l>
<l ln="23      ">Requires but time</l>
<l ln="24      ">To reach perfection.</l>
<l ln="25      ">&indent;But time plays tricks with men.</l>
<l ln="26      ">At thirty I acquired a back</l>
<l ln="27      ">That crippled <hi r="italic">me.</hi></l>
<l ln="28      ">&indent;It never is enough</l>
<l ln="29      ">Good should be done</l>
<l ln="30      ">At best a youthful fancy</l>
<l ln="31      ">Worst an act of pride,</l>
<l ln="32      ">God must be worshipped first.</l>
<l ln="33      ">So I forsook good works</l>
<l ln="34      ">With small remorse</l>
<l ln="35      ">Trying with impure mind</l>
<l ln="36      ">To find pure thought.</l>
<l ln="37      ">&indent;A foolish fancy.</l>
<l ln="38      ">I was aware, I knew</l>
<l ln="39      ">God was about me&mdash;</l>
<l ln="40      ">As He is round us all&mdash;</l>
<l ln="41      ">But where was the side</l>
<l ln="42      ">To place my finger in?</l>
<l ln="43      ">&indent;Love lost, I labour</l>
<l ln="44      ">At a foolish craft.</l>
<l ln="45      ">My hardening veins</l>
<l ln="46      ">Cry to my fatty heart</l>
<l ln="47      ">Enough!</l>
<l ln="48      ">&indent;Bones not fit for blood</l>
<l ln="49      ">Splinter and crack.</l>
<l ln="50      ">I am alone.</l>
<l ln="51      ">How can I cry</l>
<l ln="52      ">For what I seldom show</l>
<l ln="53      ">My fellow men?</l>
<pb n="74">
<l ln="54      ">Making my foolish marks</l>
<l ln="55      ">On scraps of paper</l>
<l ln="56      ">I foolishly believe</l>
<l ln="57      ">God moves my fingers.</l>
<l ln="58      ">&indent;It is the offertory hymn.</l>
<l ln="59      ">The warden with the bag</l>
<l ln="60      ">Stands waiting at the pew.</l>
<l ln="61      ">But what have I to give</l>
<l ln="62      ">The priest can bless?</l>
<l ln="63      ">A coin</l>
<l ln="64      ">No contrite heart.</l>
<l ln="65      ">&indent;The sun showers blood</l>
<l ln="66      ">Through glass on to the altar</l>
<l ln="67      ">I cannot find the key</l>
<l ln="68      ">A boyish tenor</l>
<l ln="69      ">Or a grumbling bass.</l>
<l ln="70      ">&indent;A cracked bell chimes</l>
<l ln="71      ">The candles are all snuffed.</l>
<l ln="72      ">I hear a voice</l>
<l ln="73      ">&ldquo;Come, I will give you rest&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="74      ">But feet refuse to move.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="75      ">&indent;In the garden</l>
<l ln="76      ">The nightingale</l>
<l ln="77      ">Sings all day</l>
<l ln="78      ">But I am dumb</l>
<l ln="79      ">Nothing to say.</l>
<l ln="80      ">&indent;You, dear friend</l>
<l ln="81      ">Have certainties</l>
<l ln="82      ">God will forgive</l>
<l ln="83      ">The common pride;</l>
<l ln="84      ">There is love in your eye</l>
<l ln="85      ">And a soft voice.</l>
<l ln="86      ">&indent;Perfection is not</l>
<l ln="87      ">&indent;The only key to Heaven.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="75">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546899</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>She Doesn't Sing</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546899</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>She Doesn't Sing</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000081</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000081</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>She Doesn't Sing</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">She doesn't sing</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">When I'm sat</l>
<l ln="3        ">In the room.</l>
<l ln="4        ">The whole damn world</l>
<l ln="5        ">Could turn into</l>
<l ln="6        ">The sound of singing birds</l>
<l ln="7        ">Trilling in treble</l>
<l ln="8        ">Booming out in bass</l>
<l ln="9        ">Nightingales</l>
<l ln="10      ">A towering descant.</l>
<l ln="11      ">She doesn't sing</l>
<l ln="12      ">When I'm sat</l>
<l ln="13      ">In the room.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="14      ">She doesn't laugh</l>
<l ln="15      ">When I'm sat</l>
<l ln="16      ">In the room.</l>
<l ln="17      ">But should I</l>
<l ln="18      ">Take to bed</l>
<l ln="19      ">With boredom or</l>
<l ln="20      ">A hangover</l>
<l ln="21      ">And leave her</l>
<l ln="22      ">Sitting staring</l>
<l ln="23      ">At the box,</l>
<l ln="24      ">Laughter ascends</l>
<l ln="25      ">The stairwell</l>
<l ln="26      ">&indent;And I weep.</l></pdiv>
