<newatts><attidref>X2000085</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Wise Dog</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">A wise dog</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Raises a</l>
<l ln="3        ">Paw when his</l>
<l ln="4        ">God appears.</l>
<l ln="5        ">&indent;Precaution is</l>
<l ln="6        ">The order</l>
<l ln="7        ">Of the day.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="79">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546904</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Lies and Dreams</mainhead> <attbytes>33Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546904</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Lies and Dreams</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000086</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000086</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Lies and Dreams</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>33Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<dedicat r="italic">For Fraser Steel</dedicat>
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546905</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

1 <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546905</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Lies and Dreams</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I have visited</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">This street before</l>
<l ln="3        ">Wandered past the newsagents</l>
<l ln="4        ">Inspected black ties</l>
<l ln="5        ">At an obsequious tailor's</l>
<l ln="6        ">&ldquo;A sad occasion, sir.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="7        ">Nodding I place a</l>
<l ln="8        ">Noose around my neck</l>
<l ln="9        ">Finger the material.</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;Caught at the supermarket</l>
<l ln="11      ">She stands a supplicant</l>
<l ln="12      ">At my side. Death</l>
<l ln="13      ">And his outriders</l>
<l ln="14      ">Crash across her face</l>
<l ln="15      ">&ldquo;Did you mind my ringing?&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="16      ">I shake my head and notice</l>
<l ln="17      ">The weekly fluctuation</l>
<l ln="18      ">Of food prices.</l></div3>
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546906</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

2 <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546906</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Lies and Dreams</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<l ln="19      ">That year I did</l>
<l ln="20      ">Not find the Spring</l>
<l ln="21      ">Neither was the</l>
<l ln="22      ">Peace of God</l>
<l ln="23      ">Evident.</l>
<l ln="24      ">&indent;The sacraments were</l>
<l ln="25      ">Observed in Coca Cola;</l>
<l ln="26      ">&ldquo;Take of this cup, drink</l>
<l ln="27      ">Of the silent masses.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="28      ">&indent;No one bathed</l>
<l ln="29      ">My suppurating sores</l>
<l ln="30      ">And my heart</l>
<l ln="31      ">was vexed.</l>
<l ln="32      ">Justice and mercy</l>
<l ln="33      ">Were abroad</l>
<pb n="80">
<l ln="34      ">For the summer.</l>
<l ln="35      ">Beauty was vanished</l>
<l ln="36      ">From the face of the earth.</l>
<l ln="37      ">&indent;I cried</l>
<l ln="38      ">For</l>
<l ln="39      ">The peace of God</l>
<l ln="40      ">Was not evident</l>
<l ln="41      ">And had it been</l>
<l ln="42      ">My evil eyes were</l>
<l ln="43      ">Fixed elsewhere.</l></div3>
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546907</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

3 <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546907</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Lies and Dreams</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<l ln="44      ">For some months now</l>
<l ln="45      ">I have avoided</l>
<l ln="46      ">The day. Kept at</l>
<l ln="47      ">Bay the light</l>
<l ln="48      ">Lying knee to nose</l>
<l ln="49      ">A writhing lump</l>
<l ln="50      ">Beneath thin rugs</l>
<l ln="51      ">Until night has</l>
<l ln="52      ">Unpacked its stars</l>
<l ln="53      ">And chaos.</l>
<l ln="54      ">&indent;The day is</l>
<l ln="55      ">Too beautiful</l>
<l ln="56      ">For my imagination.</l>
<l ln="57      ">Grass, young girls</l>
<l ln="58      ">Movement of trees</l>
<l ln="59      ">The sun brands</l>
<l ln="60      ">My sad eyes.</l>
<l ln="61      ">&indent;Night and the starlight</l>
<l ln="62      ">Find me at the bar</l>
<l ln="63      ">Or striding empty streets</l>
<l ln="64      ">Clad in a long coat</l>
<l ln="65      ">Dark glasses hiding</l>
<l ln="66      ">Eyes that ask for love.</l>
<l ln="67      ">Never again shall I</l>
<l ln="68      ">Stable that stallion</l>
<l ln="69      ">In my stalls.</l>
<l ln="70      ">&indent;In the ginnel</l>
<l ln="71      ">Underfoot</l>
<pb n="81">
<l ln="72      ">The glass</l>
<l ln="73      ">Crackles like ice.</l>
<l ln="74      ">&indent;Past Mirfield</l>
<l ln="75      ">Beyond, into</l>
<l ln="76      ">The Pennines</l>
<l ln="77      ">Arterial veins</l>
<l ln="78      ">Run filled</l>
<l ln="79      ">With Sci. Fi. blood.</l>
<l ln="80      ">In this uncharted land</l>
<l ln="81      ">Children learn</l>
<l ln="82      ">From loving parents</l>
<l ln="83      ">How to hate.</l>
<l ln="84      ">&indent;The church stands</l>
<l ln="85      ">On a hump</l>
<l ln="86      ">To reach it one</l>
<l ln="87      ">Must walk through</l>
<l ln="88      ">Sewage farm</l>
<l ln="89      ">Or rubbish tip.</l>
<l ln="90      ">&indent;The House of God</l>
<l ln="91      ">Was built for those</l>
<l ln="92      ">Who fall into the shit.</l></div3>
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546908</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

4 <attbytes>4Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546908</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Lies and Dreams</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<l ln="93      ">Killkof had not been</l>
<l ln="94      ">Out of late; the word</l>
<l ln="95      ">Was hard, a man was</l>
<l ln="96      ">Going round taking names.</l>
<l ln="97      ">Killkof did not wish</l>
<l ln="98      ">To give his name.</l>
<l ln="99      ">&indent;Idle, at home, the devil</l>
<l ln="100    ">Sat decorously on his shoulder,</l>
<l ln="101    ">He smiled to think a queer</l>
<l ln="102    ">Should have been honoured by a queen!</l>
<l ln="103    ">But this was jealousy, a sad</l>
<l ln="104    ">Complaint common to men of letters.</l>
<l ln="105    ">&indent;The devil never spoke</l>
<l ln="106    ">And seldom thought</l>
<l ln="107    ">What need was there when Killkof</l>
<l ln="108    ">Did both for him.</l>
<l ln="109    ">&indent;&ldquo;I know a barber's</l>
<pb n="82">
<l ln="110    ">Where the hair oil flows.</l>
<l ln="111    ">Proprietor and assistant</l>
<l ln="112    ">Men from a warmer clime</l>
<l ln="113    ">Cyprus, a lewd island</l>
<l ln="114    ">Known to Venus.</l>
<l ln="115    ">Their features swarthy</l>
<l ln="116    ">Hair curly and black</l>
<l ln="117    ">Yet all the perfume</l>
<l ln="118    ">Of Arabia</l>
<l ln="119    ">Cannot disguise</l>
<l ln="120    ">The garlic on their breath.</l>
<l ln="121    ">&indent;The atmosphere is</l>
<l ln="122    ">Dignified, a spirituality</l>
<l ln="123    ">Only found in churches</l>
<l ln="124    ">Or urinals.</l>
<l ln="125    ">Little or no</l>
<l ln="126    ">Profanity is heard</l>
<l ln="127    ">One is not asked</l>
<l ln="128    ">To tilt and hold</l>
<l ln="129    ">One's head at an awkward angle,</l>
<l ln="130    ">Quite the reverse, the barber</l>
<l ln="131    ">Holds the untenable position. Or</l>
<l ln="132    ">Should a slight adjustment</l>
<l ln="133    ">Be required, a deferential</l>
<l ln="134    ">Finger points the posture</l>
<l ln="135    ">So desired.</l>
<l ln="136    ">&indent;The snip and clack</l>
<l ln="137    ">Of scissors cutting at</l>
<l ln="138    ">The comb raised hair</l>
<l ln="139    ">Is conducive to a</l>
<l ln="140    ">Softening of the senses.</l>
<l ln="141    ">One can doze in a light</l>
<l ln="142    ">Dream scented sleep,</l>
<l ln="143    ">Sweetened by unguents</l>
<l ln="144    ">Made by ICI,</l>
<l ln="145    ">Safe in the knowledge</l>
<l ln="146    ">No harm can befall.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="147    ">&indent;Here Killkof hawked</l>
<l ln="148    ">&indent;And spat upon the floor</l>
<l ln="149    ">&indent;The devil sat</l>
<pb n="83">
<l ln="150    ">&indent;His eyes agog for more.</l>
<l ln="151    ">&ldquo;Should sleep still prove</l>
<l ln="152    ">Elusive, as it can, always</l>
<l ln="153    ">The barber's mirror will amuse.</l>
<l ln="154    ">Wrinkles unnoticed just a</l>
<l ln="155    ">Month before are now revealed,</l>
<l ln="156    ">A fiery pimple cocks</l>
<l ln="157    ">A gangrenous eye.</l>
<l ln="158    ">&indent;The barber concentrating on</l>
<l ln="159    ">His task is unaware</l>
<l ln="160    ">That he is now observed</l>
<l ln="161    ">Pushing his fornicating belly</l>
<l ln="162    ">Into your tingling elbow.</l>
<l ln="163    ">&indent;Let your mind distract</l>
<l ln="164    ">Itself with gels and smells</l>
