<l ln="561    ">The sitting on</l>
<l ln="562    ">The pedestal.</l>
<l ln="563    ">&ldquo;Are you all right, dad?&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="564    ">&ldquo;Ah, son, it's a mucky business!&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="565    ">&ldquo;Hold still while I wipe you,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="566    ">&ldquo;It's a mucky business!&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="567    ">&indent;Turds like tiny marbles</l>
<l ln="568    ">Leaving nothing on the paper,</l>
<l ln="569    ">The old man made as</l>
<l ln="570    ">Little mark on history.</l>
<l ln="571    ">&indent;Stomach, bowels</l>
<l ln="572    ">&indent;And bladder</l>
<l ln="573    ">&indent;The final solution.</l></div3>
<pb n="94">
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546914</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

10 <attbytes>8Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546914</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Lies and Dreams</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<l ln="574    ">You can sit and</l>
<l ln="575    ">Watch the people</l>
<l ln="576    ">Passing by</l>
<l ln="577    ">Curtains drawn back</l>
<l ln="578    ">In the quiet</l>
<l ln="579    ">Of early morning.</l>
<l ln="580    ">Dog sat on your lap</l>
<l ln="581    ">No one aware</l>
<l ln="582    ">Your eyes are</l>
<l ln="583    ">Laid upon them;</l>
<l ln="584    ">Then, mid&hyphen;October</l>
<l ln="585    ">Comes, and winter</l>
<l ln="586    ">Round the corner</l>
<l ln="587    ">Draws the curtain</l>
<l ln="588    ">On the scene.</l>
<l ln="589    ">&ldquo;Time to get</l>
<l ln="590    ">The misses up,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="591    ">I tell the dog</l>
<l ln="592    ">And we both make</l>
<l ln="593    ">For the bedroom.</l>
<l ln="594    ">&indent;Half way up</l>
<l ln="595    ">The stairs my mind</l>
<l ln="596    ">Is stunned, concussed</l>
<l ln="597    ">By a single word,</l>
<l ln="598    ">Charisma!</l>
<l ln="599    ">Demoralized</l>
<l ln="600    ">Knocked all</l>
<l ln="601    ">Of a heap.</l>
<l ln="602    ">Charisma!</l>
<l ln="603    ">I hurry down</l>
<l ln="604    ">Dog at heel.</l>
<l ln="605    ">There's a word</l>
<l ln="606    ">For you,</l>
<l ln="607    ">Beautiful!</l>
<l ln="608    ">&indent;Thumbing through the</l>
<l ln="609    ">Dictionary.</l>
<l ln="610    ">Wife mumbling</l>
<l ln="611    ">&ldquo;You might have</l>
<l ln="612    ">Spoken to me.&rdquo;</l>
<pb n="95">
<l ln="613    ">&indent;&ldquo;It's not in</l>
<l ln="614    ">The bloody book,</l>
<l ln="615    ">A quid gone</l>
<l ln="616    ">Down the drain.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="617    ">&indent;&ldquo;Eat your break&hyphen;</l>
<l ln="618    ">fast up,&rdquo; is all</l>
<l ln="619    ">She says</l>
<l ln="620    ">&indent;CHARISMA.</l>
<l ln="621    ">On the scent</l>
<l ln="622    ">Down to the Library.</l>
<l ln="623    ">&indent;I like October</l>
<l ln="624    ">It's unpredictable.</l>
<l ln="625    ">One morning and</l>
<l ln="626    ">It's mild, another</l>
<l ln="627    ">Finds a frost.</l>
<l ln="628    ">&indent;Still on the estate</l>
<l ln="629    ">Dogs peeing against</l>
<l ln="630    ">Posts, piles of paper</l>
<l ln="631    ">Lying about, old</l>
<l ln="632    ">Tins and folly sticks,</l>
<l ln="633    ">Second rate citizens</l>
<l ln="634    ">All.</l>
<l ln="635    ">&indent;Suddenly it's</l>
<l ln="636    ">Different, the</l>
<l ln="637    ">Structures still</l>
<l ln="638    ">Resemble</l>
<l ln="639    ">Council houses</l>
<l ln="640    ">But when the</l>
<l ln="641    ">Decorating's done</l>
<l ln="642    ">The Observer not</l>
<l ln="643    ">The People</l>
<l ln="644    ">Hides the scene.</l>
<l ln="645    ">It isn't &ldquo;posh&rdquo;,</l>
<l ln="646    ">It's private property.</l>
<l ln="647    ">By the time you reach</l>
<l ln="648    ">St Mary's,</l>
<l ln="649    ">Burglar alarms abound!.</l>
<l ln="650    ">&indent;Some social workers say</l>
<l ln="651    ">That morals improve</l>
<l ln="652    ">In private dwellings.</l>
<pb n="96">
<l ln="653    ">&indent;The fallen leaves</l>
<l ln="654    ">On the park path</l>
<l ln="655    ">Are all too wet</l>
<l ln="656    ">To rustle or fly.</l>
<l ln="657    ">A solitary magpie</l>
<l ln="658    ">Sits upon a branch,</l>
<l ln="659    ">That's bad</l>
<l ln="660    ">This I was told</l>
<l ln="661    ">By mother when</l>
<l ln="662    ">A lad, but another</l>
<l ln="663    ">One flies by,</l>
<l ln="664    ">Thank God for that!</l>
<l ln="665    ">&indent;Gardeners are</l>
<l ln="666    ">Taking up the tubers.</l>
<l ln="667    ">The earth is black,</l>
<l ln="668    ">Exciting.</l>
<l ln="669    ">A gardener rolls</l>
<l ln="670    ">A cigarette.</l>
<l ln="671    ">Another sticks his fork</l>
<l ln="672    ">Into the ground</l>
<l ln="673    ">Easing his arse</l>
<l ln="674    ">Over the handle.</l>
<l ln="675    ">They talk among</l>
<l ln="676    ">Themselves, but I pass</l>
<l ln="677    ">By without a word.</l>
<l ln="678    ">Mornings like this</l>
<l ln="679    ">And there's no need</l>
<l ln="680    ">For words.</l>
<l ln="681    ">&indent;If it was raining</l>
<l ln="682    ">That would be quite</l>
<l ln="683    ">Different, a</l>
<l ln="684    ">&ldquo;Nasty morning.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="685    ">&ldquo;Not a pleasant day,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="686    ">&ldquo;Fair pissing it down,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="687    ">&ldquo;Winter's on its way,&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="688    ">Are civil greetings.</l>
<l ln="689    ">Know your man, find</l>
<l ln="690    ">The appropriate phrase</l>
<l ln="691    ">But not this morning.</l>
<l ln="692    ">&indent;All is voluptuous.</l>
<pb n="97">
<l ln="693    ">That's a good word</l>
<l ln="694    ">Not quite right</l>
<l ln="695    ">But lovely on</l>
<l ln="696    ">The tongue,</l>
<l ln="697    ">Rich sounding.</l>
<l ln="698    ">&indent;On the pond</l>
<l ln="699    ">Ducks all dunking</l>
<l ln="700    ">Their heads,</l>
<l ln="701    ">Lovely on water</l>
<l ln="702    ">Ungainly birds on land.</l>
<l ln="703    ">Sometimes I sit and</l>
<l ln="704    ">Watch them as they</l>
<l ln="705    ">Navigate the seas,</l>
<l ln="706    ">But not today.</l>
<l ln="707    ">&indent;Out of the park gates</l>
<l ln="708    ">On down Catholic Hill,</l>
<l ln="709    ">That's not its proper</l>
<l ln="710    ">Name, but old folks</l>
<l ln="711    ">Call it that because</l>
<l ln="712    ">The church is there.</l>
<l ln="713    ">At the pub opposite</l>
<l ln="714    ">Joe's rattling the empties.</l>
<l ln="715    ">&indent;I was on my seventh pint</l>
<l ln="716    ">Chatting to someone when</l>
<l ln="717    ">There's a daughter at the door</l>
<l ln="718    ">Telegram in her hand,</l>
<l ln="719    ">&ldquo;Mandy's killed in car crash</l>
<l ln="720    ">Bob and Jane safe&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="721    ">My eldest girl's child</l>
<l ln="722    ">Just a fortnight old.</l>
<l ln="723    ">Dead!</l>
<l ln="724    ">You can't get at Him</l>
<l ln="725    ">As He broods</l>
<l ln="726    ">Among His children.</l>
<l ln="727    ">He moves his pawns</l>
<l ln="728    ">And watches the reaction.</l>
<l ln="729    ">Tears streamed down my</l>
<l ln="730    ">Face, hate bit my heart.</l>
<l ln="731    ">I don't drink there these days.</l>
<l ln="732    ">&indent;The dual carriage</l>
<pb n="98">
<l ln="733    ">Way was thick</l>
<l ln="734    ">With foul smelling</l>
<l ln="735    ">Diesel fumes.</l>
<l ln="736    ">I tried to find a</l>
<l ln="737    ">Gap between the lorries</l>
<l ln="738    ">Before breathing,</l>
<l ln="739    ">But a man could</l>
<l ln="740    ">Die that way</l>
<l ln="741    ">Suffocate before</l>
<l ln="742    ">He could inhale.</l>
<l ln="743    ">&indent;Approaching the library now.</l>
<l ln="744    ">In a sweat. Sometimes</l>
<l ln="745    ">I think I'll topple</l>
<l ln="746    ">Over the edge</l>
<l ln="747    ">Of my control,</l>
<l ln="748    ">Past toleration point.</l>
<l ln="749    ">&indent;Pulling the Oxford</l>
<l ln="750    ">Dictionary out</l>
<l ln="751    ">Palms clammy</l>
<l ln="752    ">Legs shaking</l>
<l ln="753    ">I take it to</l>
<l ln="754    ">A table.</l>
<l ln="755    ">&indent;I'd got there,</l>
<l ln="756    ">It's an achievement,</l>
<l ln="757    ">The keeping going</l>
<l ln="758    ">To the end of day.</l>
<l ln="759    ">&indent;But what had I gone for?</l>
<l ln="760    ">The word had vanished</l>
<l ln="761    ">From my mind like</l>
<l ln="762    ">Birdsong from the world.</l>
<l ln="763    ">O that beautiful word,</l>
<l ln="764    ">That delectable word,</l>
<l ln="765    ">&indent;What has the</l>
<l ln="766    ">&indent;Beginning done</l>
<l ln="767    ">&indent;With my word?</l></div3>
<div3><comhd3><idref>Z300546915</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

11 <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300546915</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Lies and Dreams</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<l ln="768    ">Never go back</l>
<l ln="769    ">To Chester</l>
<pb n="99">
<l ln="770    ">Says my head,</l>
<l ln="771    ">Frightened all</l>
<l ln="772    ">Day, scared half to death</l>
<l ln="773    ">In bed.</l>
<l ln="774    ">&indent;Down by the Dee</l>
<l ln="775    ">Fishermen</l>
<l ln="776    ">Sieve the water</l>
<l ln="777    ">With their nets.</l>
<l ln="778    ">If I walked into</l>
<l ln="779    ">The stream they'd</l>
<l ln="780    ">Make no profit</l>
<l ln="781    ">Out of me.</l>
<l ln="782    ">It's no Jordan</l>
<l ln="783    ">For seeking out</l>
<l ln="784    ">A pardon.</l>
<l ln="785    ">&indent;Devastated</l>
<l ln="786    ">With innocence,</l>
<l ln="787    ">At thirteen</l>
<l ln="788    ">Never out of love</l>
<l ln="789    ">Held in a vice</l>
<l ln="790    ">Of guilt by</l>
<l ln="791    ">The hand of love.</l>
<l ln="792    ">&indent;Now beside</l>
<l ln="793    ">Another river</l>
<l ln="794    ">The Calder</l>
<l ln="795    ">Life is more complicated.</l>
<l ln="796    ">I am not aware of love</l>
<l ln="797    ">Nor of being</l>
<l ln="798    ">Loved.</l>
<l ln="799    ">&indent;I will go</l>
<l ln="800    ">To the waters</l>
<l ln="801    ">Of my river.</l>
<l ln="802    ">Of its slime</l>
<l ln="803    ">And putrid smell</l>
<l ln="804    ">My blubbermouth</l>
<l ln="805    ">Shall drink.</l>
<l ln="806    ">Self&hyphen;deceit and</l>
<l ln="807    ">Pride will not</l>
<l ln="808    ">Defile its flow.</l>
<l ln="809    ">I will take</l>
<pb n="100">
<l ln="810    ">My sores to</l>
<l ln="811    ">The open sewer</l>
<l ln="812    ">Of hope,</l>
<l ln="813    ">Christ has been known</l>
<l ln="814    ">To search for</l>
<l ln="815    ">Sinners there,</l>
<l ln="816    ">For His Mother's sake.</l></div3>
