<newatts><attidref>X2000105</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Poem [Poor young girl]</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Poor young girl</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Poor young girl</l>
<l ln="3        ">Caught on the horn</l>
<l ln="4        ">Of a young man's dilemma</l>
<l ln="5        ">Poor young girl.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200546943</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead><hi r="italic">Poem</hi> [&ldquo;Look!&rdquo; She raised an arm]</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546943</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Poem [&ldquo;Look!&rdquo; She raised an arm]</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000106</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000106</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Poem [&ldquo;Look!&rdquo; She raised an arm]</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;Look!&rdquo; She raised an arm</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Pointing into the distant hills,</l>
<l ln="3        ">And her dress fell round her body</l>
<l ln="4        ">In lines that disturbed my crutch.</l>
<l ln="5        ">There being no one in sight,</l>
<l ln="6        ">The evening late, I placed</l>
<l ln="7        ">A hand over her breasts and we collapsed</l>
<l ln="8        ">An untidy tangle in the bracken.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546944</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Dreaming</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546944</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Dreaming</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000107</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000107</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Dreaming</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">I would have been</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Happy to be the man</l>
<l ln="3        ">Leaning against the wall</l>
<l ln="4        ">As Fred Astaire danced,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Cameras in attendance,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Down Park Avenue.</l>
<l ln="7        ">Or a chorus boy,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Some poor hoofer</l>
<l ln="9        ">Full frontal grin in view,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Filling the back row</l>
<l ln="11      ">In a Dick Power movie.</l>
<l ln="12      ">It would have been an honour</l>
<l ln="13      ">To be knocked down</l>
<pb n="138">
<l ln="14      ">By Gary Cooper's horse</l>
<l ln="15      ">As it loped through arid</l>
<l ln="16      ">Western towns pursuing villainy,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Coop,&mdash;tall in the saddle.</l>
<l ln="18      ">Yup.</l>
<l ln="19      ">Or waiting table</l>
<l ln="20      ">In Fortysecond Street,</l>
<l ln="21      ">Serve Lester Young a shot of rye</l>
<l ln="22      ">And listen to Roy Eldridge</l>
<l ln="23      ">Blowing <hi r="italic">Hecklers Hop.</hi></l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="24      ">But destiny had other plans for me.</l>
<l ln="25      ">At fourteen a fashion shop</l>
<l ln="26      ">In Boar Lane, Leeds,</l>
<l ln="27      ">Dressed in striped trousers:</l>
<l ln="28      ">Monkey jacket and white shirt:</l>
<l ln="29      ">Hair in subjection to Macassar oil.</l>
<l ln="30      ">One who jumped</l>
<l ln="31      ">At the shop assistant's cry,</l>
<l ln="32      ">&ldquo;Windows, Mr Ashby!&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="33      ">Star&hyphen;eyed and dreaming my youth away</l>
<l ln="34      ">Pleating diamante&hyphen;covered evening gowns.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200546945</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead><hi r="italic">Poem</hi> [&ldquo;Ah&rdquo;]</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546945</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Poem [&ldquo;Ah&rdquo;]</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000108</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000108</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Poem [&ldquo;Ah&rdquo;]</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;Ah&rdquo;</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The man I thought</l>
<l ln="3        ">That I would be,</l>
<l ln="4        ">&ldquo;Oh&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="5        ">The man I am.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="139">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546946</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Two Old Men</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546946</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Two Old Men</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000109</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000109</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Two Old Men</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">His bedroom smells</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of dirty clothes and</l>
<l ln="3        ">Piddled&hyphen;in pants.</l>
<l ln="4        ">As one eats breakfast</l>
<l ln="5        ">The chamber pot</l>
<l ln="6        ">Is poured into</l>
<l ln="7        ">The porcelain before</l>
<l ln="8        ">His first appearance.</l>
<l ln="9        ">It's a desperate</l>
<l ln="10      ">Situation. One</l>
<l ln="11      ">Sees oneself a</l>
<l ln="12      ">Few short years ahead,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Incontinent,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Staggering from</l>
<l ln="15      ">Chair to chair.</l>
<l ln="16      ">Respected for</l>
<l ln="17      ">One's length of</l>
<l ln="18      ">Days and depth</l>
<l ln="19      ">Of pocket.</l>
<l ln="20      ">I hate him</l>
<l ln="21      ">And he knows.</l>
<l ln="22      ">To hide the fact</l>
<l ln="23      ">A bottle of gin</l>
<l ln="24      ">Lies beside my bed</l>
<l ln="25      ">He keeps the</l>
<l ln="26      ">Stereo on loud.</l>
<l ln="27      ">Half pissed, half</l>
<l ln="28      ">Deafened I try</l>
<l ln="29      ">To be a credit</l>
<l ln="30      ">To his daughter.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="140">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546947</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Blackbird</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546947</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Blackbird</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000110</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000110</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Blackbird</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Blackbird, singing in</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The wet, bare branches</l>
<l ln="3        ">Of my tree,</l>
<l ln="4        ">Take your song</l>
<l ln="5        ">And when the sun</l>
<l ln="6        ">Issues its challenge</l>
<l ln="7        ">To the day,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Tell the good folk</l>
<l ln="9        ">Of Heckmondwike</l>
<l ln="10      ">That I too am aware</l>
<l ln="11      ">Life might have been</l>
<l ln="12      ">Other than it is.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200546948</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead><hi r="italic">Poem</hi> [It's hard to put the words down&mdash;]</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546948</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Poem [It's hard to put the words down&mdash;]</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000111</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000111</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Poem [It's hard to put the words down&mdash;]</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">It's hard to put the words down&mdash;</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Not the physical effort,</l>
<l ln="3        ">But the demand for truth</l>
<l ln="4        ">Makes every word suspect.</l>
<l ln="5        ">So poetry is lies and half&hyphen;truths</l>
<l ln="6        ">A reflection of us all,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Though I can only speak for myself.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546949</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>A Tragic Tale</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546949</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>A Tragic Tale</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000112</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000112</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>A Tragic Tale</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">And he would have told her</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Of his love</l>
<l ln="3        ">In the dog days of summer</l>
<l ln="4        ">Briar roses clambering</l>
<l ln="5        ">Up the hawthorn</l>
<l ln="6        ">The Nidd strolling quietly</l>
<l ln="7        ">Down to Knaresborough.</l>
<l ln="8        ">He, foot clumsy collar tight</l>
<l ln="9        ">Filled with prayer meeting passion</l>
<pb n="141">
<l ln="10      ">Would have told her</l>
<l ln="11      ">Of his love.</l>
<l ln="12      ">But she</l>
<l ln="13      ">All proud and delicate</l>
<l ln="14      ">Made conversation with</l>
<l ln="15      ">Her eldest sister,</l>
<l ln="16      ">Ignored the timid youth</l>
<l ln="17      ">Who trailed behind</l>
<l ln="18      ">Except when swooping on</l>
<l ln="19      ">A buttercup or Soldiers Button</l>
<l ln="20      ">Crying with ecstasy at</l>
<l ln="21      ">Some fish leaping for a fly.</l>
<l ln="22      ">&indent;And so they came to Bilton</l>
<l ln="23      ">Mumbling inexperienced goodbyes,</l>
<l ln="24      ">Saying they might meet at</l>
<l ln="25      ">Morning service, Dragon Parade.</l>
<l ln="26      ">Then they went home.</l>
<l ln="27      ">She to cold potatoes and cold meat</l>
<l ln="28      ">A mother's relentless eye</l>
<l ln="29      ">He to scones spread thick</l>
<l ln="30      ">With oven&hyphen;cooked bacon.</l>
<l ln="31      ">Mouth full but unreproached&mdash;</l>
<l ln="32      ">For was he not the youngest</l>
<l ln="33      ">And were not his bad manners</l>
<l ln="34      ">Forgiven before committed&mdash;</l>
<l ln="35      ">He blurted out</l>
<l ln="36      ">&ldquo;I've met the girl that I intend to marry.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="37      ">Of course they were delighted</l>
<l ln="38      ">And amused.</l>
<l ln="39      ">&ldquo;Bless the boy&rdquo; said grandma,</l>
<l ln="40      ">A sister,</l>
<l ln="41      ">&ldquo;Our Harold is a card!&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="42      ">Be that as it may</l>
<l ln="43      ">There was a wedding day</l>
<l ln="44      ">And an Ashby was united</l>
<l ln="45      ">With a King.</l>
<l ln="46      ">&indent;They lived their loveless days</l>
<l ln="47      ">&indent;One driven by vanity</l>
<l ln="48      ">&indent;The other pursued by fear.</l>
<l ln="49      ">&indent;Both died with little hope.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="142">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546950</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Dog Hill</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546950</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Dog Hill</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000113</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000113</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Dog Hill</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Come on, bitch</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Let's up Dog Hill</l>
<l ln="3        ">The unemployed</l>
<l ln="4        ">Exercising</l>
<l ln="5        ">The unemployable.</l>
<l ln="6        ">Above the spewing Spen</l>
<l ln="7        ">A depression of estates</l>
<l ln="8        ">Spreads over each aspiring hill,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Fields of hope diminish</l>
<l ln="10      ">The tree of joy is felled.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="11      ">At Merriscourt in harvest weather</l>
<l ln="12      ">A fox, in a feathered reverie</l>
<l ln="13      ">Strolled through my herd of cows.</l>
<l ln="14      ">The evening sun caught</l>
<l ln="15      ">Shipton under Wychwood,</l>
<l ln="16      ">All my children were asleep</l>
<l ln="17      ">And love seemed not a lie.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="18      ">She sympathized&mdash;</l>
<l ln="19      ">&ldquo;At sixtyfour</l>
<l ln="20      ">You can't do more</l>
<l ln="21      ">Than what you did</l>
<l ln="22      ">Around a score.&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="23      ">And I knew that I was old.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="24      ">One two three</l>
<l ln="25      ">Magpies in a tree</l>
<l ln="26      ">What's to become of me?</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="143">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546951</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Easter Skipping Song</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546951</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Easter Skipping Song</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000114</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000114</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Easter Skipping Song</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<dedicat r="italic">For Sonali</dedicat>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Christ is up with a hobbledeho</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Tripmalarityganzy</l>
<l ln="3        ">Six of His salesmen stood in a row</l>
<l ln="4        ">Tripmalarityganzy</l>
<l ln="5        ">A spinster opens the door a crack</l>
<l ln="6        ">Tripmalarityganzy</l>
<l ln="7        ">Two kestrels mate on the chimney stack</l>
<l ln="8        ">Tripmalarityganzy</l>
<l ln="9        ">The sun comes out with a &ldquo;view halloo&rdquo;</l>
<l ln="10      ">Tripmalarityganzy</l>
<l ln="11      ">The seagulls howl and the dogs all mew</l>
<l ln="12      ">Tripmalarityganzy</l>
<l ln="13      ">When I am old I'll sit in a chair</l>
<l ln="14      ">Tripmalarityganzy</l>
<l ln="15      ">My grandaughters two will wash my hair</l>
<l ln="16      ">Tripmalarityganzy</l>
<l ln="17      ">With water drawn from the crystal Spen</l>
<l ln="18      ">Tripmalarity ganzy</l>
<l ln="19      ">Pig in a palace pope in a pen</l>
<l ln="20      ">Tripmalarityganzy.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546952</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Hindsight</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546952</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Hindsight</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000115</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000115</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Hindsight</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">When sight was sound</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">And every sound was relayed</l>
<l ln="3        ">To the senses, life seemed endless</l>
<l ln="4        ">And each moment missing from</l>
<l ln="5        ">The loved one an eternity.</l>
<l ln="6        ">But now my darling reading</l>
<l ln="7        ">The obituaries it seems, friends</l>
<l ln="8        ">Fade like flowers and every face</l>
<l ln="9        ">One confronts in the street</l>
<l ln="10      ">May look familiar but must be</l>
<l ln="11      ">Dead or different.</l>
<pb n="144">
<l ln="12      ">&indent;Where is that goal of peace</l>
<l ln="13      ">&indent;That we pursued?</l>
<l ln="14      ">Now eyes strain, ears are on the wane</l>
<l ln="15      ">The aches and pain of age</l>
<l ln="16      ">Rock us as with calloused feet</l>
<l ln="17      ">We stumble towards anonymity.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546953</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>I Start</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546953</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>I Start</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000116</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000116</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>I Start</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I do nothing</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Earlier than I did</l>
<l ln="3        ">A year ago,</l>
<l ln="4        ">I need a longer day</l>
<l ln="5        ">To get my worrying done.</l>
<l ln="6        ">Under occupied,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Over indulged,</l>
<l ln="8        ">When the gin starts to work</l>
<l ln="9        ">Stand by your telephones, friends,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Ashby is on the prowl asking for love.</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;It's doubtful if you'll</l>
<l ln="12      ">&indent;Get a hint of his.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546954</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>The Fisherman's Daughter Peel</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546954</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>The Fisherman's Daughter Peel</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000117</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000117</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>The Fisherman's Daughter Peel</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I would walk down Derby Road</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Holding my love a secret,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Eyes on my clumsy boots in fear</l>
<l ln="4        ">Someone should see into my heart.</l>
<l ln="5        ">Or laid in bed conjure up her face;</l>
<l ln="6        ">Brown eyes that spoke to me alone,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Or so I thought:</l>
<l ln="8        ">Black hair I dare not touch&mdash;</l>
<l ln="9        ">Not even in a dream.</l>
<pb n="145">
<l ln="10      ">Should we pass along the harbour wall</l>
<l ln="11      ">Or in school corridor, so weak my legs</l>
<l ln="12      ">I thought that I would faint.</l>
<l ln="13      ">A curse upon my non&hyphen;conformist nose</l>
<l ln="14      ">Offended by the smell of her father's trade.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546955</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>War Poem</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546955</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>War Poem</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000118</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000118</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>War Poem</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Her face was calm</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Her body had the lines of grace.</l>
<l ln="3        ">&ldquo;Who&rdquo; I asked, &ldquo;is that gentlewoman</l>
<l ln="4        ">Riding so often into Kintbury?&rdquo;</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="5        ">&indent;She had five children.</l>
<l ln="6        ">&indent;Two by her husband</l>
<l ln="7        ">&indent;One in a union with some U.S. serviceman</l>
<l ln="8        ">&indent;Two more by her father.</l>
<l ln="9        ">&indent;He, when learning of her intended marriage</l>
<l ln="10      ">&indent;Took her and shotgun into a distant field</l>
<l ln="11      ">&indent;Blasted one barrel in her face</l>
<l ln="12      ">&indent;Then blew himself away.</l>
<l ln="13      ">&indent;She lived face scarred</l>
<l ln="14      ">&indent;Vanishing into London</l>
<l ln="15      ">&indent;A week or more at a time</l>
<l ln="16      ">&indent;With some lost soul from Arkansas</l>
<l ln="17      ">&indent;Or Tallahassee.</l>
<l ln="18      ">&indent;Always returning to tend her young</l>
<l ln="19      ">&indent;She faced the hamlet with indifferent pride.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="20      ">A more incestuous clutter of cottages</l>
<l ln="21      ">The killing soil never revealed to me,</l>
<l ln="22      ">But I was happy there</l>
<l ln="23      ">Made aware of my true depravity.</l>
<l ln="24      ">Surrounded by men who never found toil</l>
<l ln="25      ">A panacea for living</l>
<l ln="26      ">Unable to differentiate between the two.</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="146">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2><idref>Z200546956</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead><hi r="italic">Poem</hi> [I am too much]</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546956</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Poem [I am too much]</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000119</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000119</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Poem [I am too much]</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">I am too much</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Like a man</l>
<l ln="3        ">I do not admire.</l>
<l ln="4        ">Quick to anger</l>
<l ln="5        ">Speaking ill</l>
<l ln="6        ">Of everyone</l>
<l ln="7        ">Satisfied with nothing</l>
<l ln="8        ">Loving nobody.</l>
<l ln="9        ">&indent;Look! the lilac has come out.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546957</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Heckmondwike Poem</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546957</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Heckmondwike Poem</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000120</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000120</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Heckmondwike Poem</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">There is a confusion</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">In my head. A madness</l>
<l ln="3        ">As chaotic as the universe</l>
<l ln="4        ">Before the mind of God</l>
<l ln="5        ">Brought order to the stars</l>
<l ln="6        ">And put each living creature</l>
<l ln="7        ">In its proper place.</l>
<l ln="8        ">There is a confusion</l>
<l ln="9        ">In my heart where love</l>
<l ln="10      ">Longing to spread about</l>
<l ln="11      ">The objects that my eye perceives</l>
<l ln="12      ">Remains locked in the prison</l>
<l ln="13      ">Of my sad timidity.</l>
<l ln="14      ">Another May&mdash;the rhododendrons weep.</l>
<l ln="15      ">Love hardens in the young</l>
<l ln="16      ">And age attempts again</l>
<l ln="17      ">To square its shoulders.</l>
<l ln="18      ">Winter has passed</l>
<l ln="19      ">But spring can still</l>
<l ln="20      ">Do violence to the old.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<pb n="147">
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546958</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>On Seeing Hall Caine Peel&mdash;I.O.M.&mdash;1920s</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546958</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>On Seeing Hall Caine Peel&mdash;I.O.M.&mdash;1920s</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000121</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000121</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>On Seeing Hall Caine Peel&mdash;I.O.M.&mdash;1920s</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">He was standing</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">One foot upon</l>
<l ln="3        ">The promenade's bottom rail</l>
<l ln="4        ">Looking towards</l>
<l ln="5        ">The Mull of Galloway.</l>
<l ln="6        ">It was winter&mdash;quiet</l>
<l ln="7        ">The sea so still</l>
<l ln="8        ">Sky bluer than now.</l>
<l ln="9        ">I think he wore a cloak</l>
<l ln="10      ">A funny hat, a beard,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Certainly he was different</l>
<l ln="12      ">Displaying an absorption</l>
<l ln="13      ">That confounded me.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="14      ">&indent;Everything so still</l>
<l ln="15      ">&indent;And I so young.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="16      ">Perhaps I imagined this</l>
<l ln="17      ">Or heard someone describe the scene?</l>
<l ln="18      ">It is vague&mdash;</l>
<l ln="19      ">As are my memories</l>
<l ln="20      ">Of being a child.</l>
<l ln="21      ">&indent;Was I ever younger</l>
<l ln="22      ">&indent;Than I am now?</l></pdiv>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546959</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Friends</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546959</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Friends</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000122</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000122</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Friends</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">When you reach old age</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Don't try to find lost friends.</l>
<l ln="3        ">It seems the best are dead</l>
<l ln="4        ">Those left not as remembered</l>
<l ln="5        ">While some shout through the keyhole</l>
<l ln="6        ">&ldquo;Go away&rdquo;.</l>
<pb n="148">
<l ln="7        ">I search among the people in the street</l>
<l ln="8        ">For unlined faces</l>
<l ln="9        ">Such as I imagine mine to be</l>
<l ln="10      ">And meet old age, stooped shoulders</l>
<l ln="11      ">Generous figures and ungenerous minds.</l>
<l ln="12      ">It seems that friendship</l>
<l ln="13      ">Starts with admiration,</l>
<l ln="14      ">Grows into a comfortable habit,</l>
<l ln="15      ">Then desiccates and dies.</l>
<l ln="16      ">Those I once loved</l>
<l ln="17      ">I find I now despise.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546960</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Not Every Seed</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546960</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Not Every Seed</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000123</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000123</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Not Every Seed</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Not every seed that's sown turns out to be</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Fit for the show bench or a fruitful tree.</l>
<l ln="3        ">Some fall on stony ground in time of drought</l>
<l ln="4        ">Some germinate and put their seed leaves out</l>
<l ln="5        ">But fall a victim to the slug or fly</l>
<l ln="6        ">The pigeons' crop or heel of passerby.</l>
<l ln="7        ">And so with men, who in God's image made,</l>
<l ln="8        ">End up behind a desk or in some trade</l>
<l ln="9        ">Chosen by parents as a last resort</l>
<l ln="10      ">For dreaming children with a poor report.</l>
<l ln="11      ">Not to be clever is a fine disguise</l>
<l ln="12      ">For those who seek the wisdom of the wise</l>
<l ln="13      ">And turn their faces from the sickening mess</l>
<l ln="14      ">Of those who seek the wisdom of success.</l>
<poemcopy>&copy; Copyright material reproduced under licence from Carcanet Press Ltd.</poemcopy>
</poem>
</div2>
<div2>
<poem><comhd2 r="italic"><idref>Z200546961</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Ashby, Cliff.<sombiog>168</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>Green Peace</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z200546961</ID><A1>Ashby, Cliff.</A1><T1>Green Peace</T1><PBL>Carcanet</PBL><Y1>1985</Y1><T2>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd2>
<attribs><attpoet>Ashby, Cliff.</attpoet><attidref>X2000124</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>X2000124</attidref><attdbase>Modern Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century English Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>Carcanet</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>Green Peace</mainhead><volhead>Plain Song: Collected Poems: 1960&ndash;1985 (1985)<publish>, Carcanet</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1985</attpubn1><attpubn2>1985</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview><engcorp2></engcorp2></attview><attautid>168</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">&ldquo;When morning gilds the sky&rdquo;</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">It's time to gather up</l>
<l ln="3        ">One's fears and drown them</l>
<l ln="4        ">In a pint of Doctor Green.</l>
<pb n="149">
<l ln="5        ">&indent;Someone has said, I've seen</l>
<l ln="6        ">It in a book, &ldquo;The unknown</l>
<l ln="7        ">Is what man is frightened of&rdquo;.</l>
<l ln="8        ">But surfacing from oblivion</l>
<l ln="9        ">That has no dreams</l>
<l ln="10      ">Mouth in a conversation</l>
<l ln="11      ">The mind is ignorant of</l>
<l ln="12      ">In a place one can't remember</l>
<l ln="13      ">Getting to</l>
<l ln="14      ">Smiles of friendship</l>
<l ln="15      ">Drive one home to seek again</l>
<l ln="16      ">The comfort of a pint of Doctor Green.</l>
<l ln="17      ">Last year I missed the daphne</l>
<l ln="18      ">This the spring.</l>
<l ln="19      ">Days disappear in loneliness</l>
<l ln="20      ">The breakdown of affections</l>
<l ln="21      ">And the scaling off of talent</l>
<l ln="22      ">Until a pint of Doctor Green</l>
<l ln="23      ">Makes society's indifference bearable.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="24      ">One day, perhaps, the Comforter will come</l>
<l ln="25      ">Disturbing the spirits beating Salvation's drum</l>
<l ln="26      ">Or with the wisdom plucked from a dusty shelf</l>
<l ln="27      ">Suggest somewhere I have a better self.</l></pdiv>
<pdiv><l ln="28      ">If fish still swam in rivers</l>
<l ln="29      ">And the old all died in bed</l>
<l ln="30      ">If pastures were unpoisoned</l>
<l ln="31      ">And the swan was free from lead</l>
<l ln="32      ">If gay was still a lovely word</l>
<l ln="33      ">And a child was safe at play</l>
<l ln="34      ">If the chicken in the battery house</l>
<l ln="35      ">Looked forward to the day</l>
<l ln="36      ">If joy still walked abroad</l>
<l ln="37      ">And man's condition was less mean</l>
<l ln="38      ">And all the dolphins were set free</l>
<l ln="39      ">What then Doctor Green?</l></pdiv>
